Homelife_text: Growing up my family was much more observant than I (or my siblings) currently are.  We grew up going to Hebrew school 3 times/week, and Synagogue every week.  Our home was Kosher for a good chunk of my life until Jr. High, and my older brothers attended Jewish Day School (myself and my younger sister went to public elementary school).  It is very important to me that if we do have children, they are raised Jewish.  However, to me that means more culturally Jewish and Jewish in community involvement.  The religious aspect of Judaism does not appeal to either myself or my spouse.  My family still has Shabbat every week, and we intend to continue that throughout our lives whether or not we have children.  It is important to me to continue our traditions and the messages that Judaism is about, but the religion/God aspect of it does not necessarily fit our lifestyle or existential beliefs.  Part of the reason I still strongly agree with Judaism, not only on a cultural level, is because it encourages its' followers to question things and approach the religion with objectivity - which is something that we are strong proponents of and would encourage our children to do.
ChildRaise:
At this moment, we are very on the fence about having children.  We anticipate that we will probably change our mind, but we know that we need to be 100% on board and excited to do it before we make the commitment to do so.  I am currently very focused on my career and company, so it would be difficult for us to have a child in the next year or 2.  We do discuss this a lot, and have not really committed one way or another.  Adoption later on is something we have explored as well.

If we do have children, there is no question that we would raise them Jewish.  This is something we discussed very early on and agreed upon.  However, we will still celebrate Christmas with his family.
OtherText: To follow up on the last question - I would love to have a larger base of interfaith or non traditional Jewish couples.  It is extremely hard to feel included/accepted/relatable to traditional Jewish couples the majority of the time.  Most of my friends come from typical fully Jewish families, and are married to other Jews.  It is almost like living in a different world sometimes.  Still love my friends/family that fits into this, but it can be alienating.  When you don't feel accepted or included, it is hard to stay excited or interested in being Jewish.  It is definitely a turn off for my spouse - it was almost like I talked up this religion, and he went into it thinking it would be awesome.  Then when he got there, a lot of the people weren't very accepting and nice - so a lot of momentum of that excitement was lost.
Israel_text: I have been to Israel 3 times, and studied abroad there in High School (AMHSI)

JewishFam_text: It is hard to answer this in just one or two check boxes.  My spouse is not religious at all, and was not raised with a religion.  We do celebrate Christmas with his family, but they only really "celebrate" it because it's something they grew up with.  They never belonged to a church or participated in youth group, etc.  His extended family is Catholic, but my spouse has probably been inside of a Synagogue more times than he has been inside of a Church at this point. My spouse always participates in Jewish things with me, and he likes the traditions a lot.  He seems to get excited to spend Jewish holidays with my family, and bake/cook Jewish foods.  He is always interested in learning about the religion and Israel.  However, it can be difficult to make him feel welcomed because as we all know, Jews can be a little cliquey with one another.  We celebrate and practice far more Jewish things than anything else (really all we "celebrate" is Christmas, and that really just buying presents and hanging out with his family for the weekend in a non-religious way).  We are very respectful of one another's beliefs, and existentially speaking, we very much agree on where we stand as far as beliefs in God, etc.

Powerful:
There were many powerful experiences along the trip. One of the most powerful experiences was going to the Western Wall for Shabbat on the night of our arrival. We were exhausted, and I did not want to go anywhere except for bed. I had no idea how amazing the experience was going to be. It is still mind blowing for me to realize I had never been there before, but it felt like home.  That is actually how Israel felt to me, like home. 
Another powerful experience was being on the beach in Tel Aviv. There were two events that stuck out to me, one was at night, with the clear sky and the bright moon, the other was watching the most amazing sunset over the sea with my husband.

OtherText:
As someone who doesn't usually travel in a group, I am still amazed by the great balance the trip and the trip leaders struck between free time and group time, and by how they built an itinerary that had something for everyone. It is amazing to have surfed in the sun, walked Tsfat in the fog, and watched snow fall in Jerusalem. I thought the group travel dynamics of my cohort were great, and that was due in large part to the leaders. 

I was surprised by this, but I found it so much easier to connect with couples closer to my age. 

I still think a lot about the trip. I think about what we did and did not (or couldn't) see with respect to Israel/Palestine. I think a lot about the experiences where we had an opportunity to sit down and hear from a political journalist, a Haredi woman, Israeli Arabs, a Kabbalist, and Mr. Infeld -- I loved those experiences. I think about how the standard narration during the tour of Yad Vashem seemed to be constructed as though I might not believe that the Holocaust happened. I think about how many signs I saw in Jerusalem acclaiming financial support from an American. I will continue to reflect a lot on the trip, and I'll continue to learn more along with my partner.

ChildRaise:
I'm not religious, so I can't expect my children to be religious.  But I want them to understand what it means to be a Jew.  That said, I'm not sure I could define it myself.  It means being part of a people, and those people have looked and sounded a certain way for a while.  But our children are going to look different, as are a LOT of Jews born to this generation - something like 3/4 of all non-orthodox Jews are intermarrying.

I want my kids to understand the tradition they come from, and be proud of all the amazing contributions of Jews in spite of persecution - Albert Einstein, Sigmund Freud, Jerry Seinfeld, etc.  Understanding the history of the Jews, and why it's important Jews continue to exist.  That means exposure to Jewish movies, books, and people.  And I want them to have some understanding of the religion, which probably means at least a few years of religious schools.
Israel_text:
As a Jew, I feel proud of Israel.  But when I read the news, I feel less proud of Israel.

Israel has a real problem these days.  Young people, including a lot of young Jews, are really turned off by some of its actions, and the attitude from its current leadership.  I doubt that this can be changed by groups like Honeymoon Israel, Birthright or Fuel for Truth.  If Israel doesn't change its course somehow, it's going to face isolation when the next generation takes power.
Children: No, but we hope to have children in the future
JewishFam_text: I wouldn't say we're a Jewish family, or a Christian family.  I'm Jewish, and my wife is Christian.  She goes to church sometimes, I go to Jewish events sometimes.  Very rarely, I go with her, or she goes with me.  We talk openly about religion occasionally, about different religious beliefs, how they have affected history and us personally.  I'm not very religious, but I feel strongly culturally Jewish, and I try to introduce my wife to Jewish culture.  We watch movies about Jews and Israel, celebrate some Jewish holidays with my family, and talk about Jewish life with certain friends.  I very much want to raise our children Jewish, and we've agreed to do that.

Homelife_text: It is very important to me that our home reflect a marked commitment to my husband's Jewish cultural identity and having some Jewish religious symbols (mezuzot, a menorah) is a particular point of pride for me even though my husband is not at all religious. In that regard, when we have children, my goal is to provide a home that fosters strong cultural ties to Jewish culture and to Israel, and that nurtures our children's own curiosity about religion so that they can choose for themselves, whether Judaism or otherwise.
ChildRaise: By default, our children will have the greatest exposure to Judaism and Catholicism by virtue of their parents' respective backgrounds, which will be part of our lives and the traditions we develop as an interfaith family, as well. Both my husband and I agree that we will raise children with a strong cultural connection to Judaism, which will include certain religious rites like becoming a bar/bat mitzvah and, for any son we might have, a bris. That being said, we do plan to emphasize cultural Judaism over religious Judaism because my husband is not religious and in his own upbringing, Jewish holidays and rites were almost exclusively matters of family tradition rather than religious obligation. I am very committed to ensuring that our future children know about and honor their cultural ties to Judaism but also that they choose religion - whether Judaism or otherwise - for themselves and not because we have told them what to believe.
OtherText: I have really enjoyed the pre-departure get-togethers and I think Chloe Nassau, our primary point of contact with HMI, has been an amazing resource and a very positive influence on getting the group amped up. Though she won't be able to join us on our trip, both my husband and I are really excited that Jeffrey Eisner will be standing in for Chloe as he has great, warm energy, and as an HMI alum, also represents our hope that traveling to Israel is only the beginning of our connection with Honeymoon Israel for many years to come.

Homelife_text: I think this is something we will work on for a long time, particularly as circumstances change and children become the focal point of our family life. For now, I make a conscious effort to do something Jewish (loosely defined) at least once a week, whether its a social event with other HMI couples (that's the loose definition of 'something Jewish') or attending Shabbat services on a Friday evening.
ExpectPostTrip_08text: I don't know that my husband and I will ever have the opportunity to live in Israel at some point in our lives, but short of doing so, HMI has made me think about whether there are other ways to connect with Israel in a permanent and meaningful way. I have been exploring the possibility recently for my husband to exercise his right to Israeli citizenship (and, by extension, my ability to become a citizen as his spouse). I feel strongly since returning from Israel with HMI that when we have children, they will be connected to Israel not simply as Jews but as citizens of the Jewish State. And as a person who was not born and raised Jewish and thus does not have a birthright to Israeli citizenship, this is an important way for me to express my love, solidarity, and support both for the Jewish people and for Israel.
ChildRaise: We have not yet decided how we will be having children but in thinking about surrogacy and egg donors, I have wondered whether it should be important for either or both of the surrogate and egg donor to be Jewish (by birth). What is most important to me is that our children have a strong relationship with Judaism and with Israel, and I think that will be a function of my husband's and my parenting rather than whether the surrogate and/or egg donor was born a Jew. Our conversations about how we will raise our children Jewishly, including how we have them, is ongoing.
Children: No, but we hope to have children in the future
Powerful:
Every part of our HMI experience was enhanced by the presence and participation of our leadership, but most importantly, Rabbi Matt Greene. Matt was always accessible, eager to answer questions and provide his own experience and insight, and was just an all around amazing asset to all of the couples. I think what stands out to me most about Matt, and why it seemed so effortless to connect with him, was that he was effectively one of us. It never felt teacher-y with Matt. He could have easily been a participant on our trip and that made him approachable and relatable.
I would be remiss not to mention that Jeff Eisner and our Israeli educator from Da'at, Lior Hochberg, were also major contributors to our HMI experience. Again, both Jeff and Lior were relatable -- and Jeff is himself an HMI alum.
Now that I write this I realize why this all mattered so much to me -- it is because the leadership on our trip became our friends as much as all of the other couples did, and I don't think Corey and I would be the only ones to say so.
HMI was an amazing experience that we try to continue even though we've returned from Israel now, but I think what we treasure the most is the friendships with other couples and with the Matt, Jeff, and Lior.
Adjective_text: The feelings of alienation and anxiety that I said I feel slightly are a result of not having been raised Jewish and wondering whether I can do Jewish things, live a Jewish life, call myself Jewish, and whether the Jewish community will consider me a participant or just a friendly observer.

OtherText: I wish the survey asked about the experience with the staff and the process. Overall we are very disappointed in the process and feel Alienated by the folks because you don't see my wife and as  potential converts or on the fence about being Jewish. I clearly believe that is what you folks are looking for, you are looking to convert even though that is stated clearly that is not the purpose of the organization. My experiences with you folks tells me that their is very much an alternative motive and being that we literally got married and I would love nothing more than to share with my wife my cultural and what being a Jew is and looks like outside of the US with her to have a better connection to being Jewish is completely overlooked because she already has converted and has two feet in already you don't view us as candidates for the trip and that is why we have been turned down 3 times and frankly i think that is crap. During our interviews I communicated clearly that my wife and I are Jewish and committed to being Jews and it was blatantly clear that we are not going to get accepted to a trip because there is no objective with us even though I truly believe my wife would benefit much more than most folks who go on this trip with developing a stronger connection to her commitment to being a Jew.

I identify as a reform Jew with some more traditional observances. There is not really a jewish day school that follows these same beliefs (solomon schechter being conservative and egalitarian comes very close - but it is in Cote St Luc and we are in the West Island...) So I worry that Jewish education will be difficult when we have children - limited to learning in the home and maybe driving to Temple Emanu-El in Westmount for Torah school on Saturdays.
There are good Jewish summer camps, I envision sending our children to camp when they are old enough, and joining youth groups during the school year to continue their Jewish education and allow them to socialize with other Jewish children, especially if they do not end up in a Jewish day school.

JewishFam_text: Questions like this are always a little tricky for me! I?m the non-Jewish partner in the family and happen to work in Jewish education at a synagogue. I?ve been stuck in this in between space for years where I feel Jewish, or at least Jew-ish and ?pass?, but haven?t taken the steps to convert (though it?s been on my mind and my heart for years!) and feel weird saying ?Yes, we  are a Jewish family? until I take the (literal) plunge!
Powerful:
There were tons of both heavy and powerful moments on the trip?just knowing the places we walked through were home to so much shared history was very grounding. We were just talking the other day about the very end of Yad Vashem: walking out to the very last view and overlooking the mountains was incredibly powerful and in that single view, I felt like I had a new understanding of why people feel so powerfully drawn to Israel as both a place and an idea. I wish I had the words to encompass that feeling! 

I think I?ve mentioned it before, but we also had the option to participate in a Hebrew naming ceremony on our final day, overlooking the old port of Jaffa (could it get more picturesque?!?). As a non-Jew, the enthusiasm and inclusivity I was met with when I decided I wanted to be blessed with a Hebrew name was really heartwarming and I really felt like there was a place for me as an individual in that moment. The name that was suggested was perfectly fitting?it translates roughly to ?a return to G-d?, which is exactly how my partner and I left Israel: feeling more connected to our spirituality and to each other.

Homelife_text:
Understanding of our shared existence and growth at this time within the historic framework of human social evolution. From that, a relationship to ancient and modern teachings can be understood and interpreted, thus becoming a mental framework relevant for personal growth.

Its a living tradition. So in practice, the forms and rituals are useful as reminders of what it is to be human.

Our intent is that as we raise children we will enable to engage with the above. Hopefully in a way that will be meaningful and useful to them.

*Note - Its impossible for me not to be a Unitarian Universalist; this includes Judaism sans any exclusionary practices or traditions. Conveniently its all part of the same tradition.*

Homelife_text: To be perfectly honest, I am not positive what "Jewish Home Life - with Kids" will look like yet, but I do want it to be something that celebrates Jewish identity, Jewish religion and holidays, but with a healthy dose of understanding the cultural backgrounds of both parents that isn't explicitly Jewish. Not religious per se, but not uniformly Jewish, either. Again, what that looks like I am not sure, but it something I want to value and model.
ChildRaise: It may be more effective for the purposes of this survey for me to itemize what I feel is important, since it is all academic at this point! Jewish education, lifecycle ceremonies, and celebration of Jewish holidays are all very important - especially making Shabbat special. I want to raise them with a healthy sense of curiosity and confidence to question and explore their faith and culture as appropriate. I want to incorporate lessons learned from my childhood - such a growing up poor - in a way that will teach empathy and understanding. And I very much want them to associate with others who are not like them, especially socioeconomically and culturo-religiously.
OtherText: Truly, truly, truly, amazing trip. I look back at it with so much pleasure in times of challenge. I would love to be more involved in helping others be able to make the trip, as well as in helping HMI in any way that I can!
Israel_text:
Israel, and my feelings on it are...complicated. While Israel (the land) is so central to the Jewish faith, I feel strongly that so much of Jewish religious practice and development, especially liberal Judaism, developed and was refined in the Diaspora - and that an obsession with Israel discredits the notion that Judaism can be practiced in a loving and emphatic way outside of the land of Israel, though I understand the history and importance of the land. 

The country/state, however, is even more complicated. As it has been said, Israel can be a Jewish state, or it can be a democracy, but it cannot be both. And even as a Jew, I don't much care for religious-state, even if they are not traditional theocracies. I don't know if that makes me anit-Zionist, but it does put me at odds with much of the Jewish community. Thus, if Israel is to be a democracy, it is worthy of much criticism, not unlike other Western states that fail to live up to their promise, or my worldview (after all, politics is fundamentally personal). It's a marvelous and incredible country, not unlike Italy or Great Britain, with a rich history, culture, and purpose. And modern Israel (the state) was created by the Diaspora - or at least a the antisemitism that is often so rampant in it - so I love the notion that it is a homeland for Jews - but I don't love the idea of it as a Jewish State run, either de facto or de jure, under Jewish law. 

Sorry, may seem a bit of a rant but Israel, and my feelings towards it, are complicated! 

Also, Israel

Powerful: There were so many things I experienced on the trip that, especially in the aggregate, the had a profound impact on me. One that stands out was my experience at the Western Wall, where despite my overarching skepticism for the reverence of a retaining wall that seemed to border on idolatry, I nevertheless *felt* what it meant to other people, and how that shared faith and emotion could be such a powerful thing.
Adjective_text: Fundamentally, I feel curious and excited. I love joining and being part of a people with such a rich and fascinating history, but also with such a strong sense of social justice and community. Learning all about it is a true labor of love for me.

As a convert to Judaism who was first truly exposed to it through my partner, I have very few Jewish friends in the other social circles I run in - and even those who are cultural Jewish are not practicing. Thus, the "Jewishness" of my HMI friendships is was is so valuable to me - and something that it is fundamentally different. 

Put simply, I wold like HMI to know that HMI has really helped me grow my Jewish friend circle in an incredible way that would have taken years to otherwise accomplish!

I only know what I was raised with, which was a family in the Conservative movement who kept kosher and observed all holidays and occasions (including weekly Shabbat). At the minimum, I would want to acknowledge the major holidays in some way, along with some sort of family traditions around these holidays. And some sort of a Jewish education if we someday have children.

ChildRaise: I would love to find a way to incorporate Jewish traditions when raising children. I loved all of the holiday traditions that revolved around food and family and history when growing up, and would love for my kids to have that experience. Where I struggle to picture how to raise children in the Jewish faith is that both myself and my partner identify as agnostic, so the religious aspect is a bit of a disconnect for both of us. Since my partner does not identify as Jewish and does not have the same connection to the Jewish identify, we would want to find a balance so our family traditions reflect both of our upbringings.

It is important to my husband and I also think it is important to maintain Jewish culture and religion for our future children. I also do not want my children to be raised in the Catholic church, as I have many issue with the Catholic church and I was raised Catholic. Jewish home life would look like having regular Shabbat dinners, going to services regularly as a family, and maintaining a home that discusses  Jewish issues.

I want to practice Shabbat at home regularly, go to high holiday services always, sometimes go to saturday shabbat services, and engage in discussion of torah with a jewish understnding.
ChildRaise:
This is something that is not yet fully sorted out between my Wife and me.  Personally, my belief was that a trip like Honeymoon Israel could be fundamental in helping to build greater roo-ach / spirit around Jewish traditions and make it easier for Jewish upbringing to be more present.  I worry that I will have limited ability to influence a Jewish upbringing for my children even though my wife has previously committed to doing so - I think that without a stronger and ongoing connection to Jewish life, it will be too easy to stray away from it.
To me, I would like full time Jewish day school as well as weekly shabbat dinners at home, among other holidays, as core traditions.

Israel_text: I think it?s pretty clear how I (Maliha) think about Israel - like all ethnonationalist countries, the very foundations of the state are deeply racist. I find liberal Zionism (e.g. organizations like NIF) in particular to be odious in its attempts to paper over the inherently racist character of the state. It is difficult for me to authentically connect with liberal American Jews with whom I share affinities for so many things - but then they have a glaring blind spot when it comes to Israel, and no amount of reason can change their minds. And HMI, in taking participants to Israel and making the land of Israel seem like a birthright or place of significance for American Jews who have absolutely no connection to the land, contributes to this problem. Who doesn?t like privilege?

JewishFam_text:
I would describe my family as an inter-cultural one. I am Jewish and anglophone (my mother tongue is English), and my partner is French-Canadian and his mother tongue is French. Although he was baptized and confirmed in the Catholic Church, he considers himself non-practising and an atheist. It is important for us to incorporate both of our cultures into our homes, which includes celebrating the Jewish holidays (lighting the menorah, going to Purim parties, celebrating Rosh Hashanah and Passover with my family) and speaking both English and French with one another. 
I put down my answer because we primarily celebrate the Jewish holidays, and we go to his family for Christmas. I would like to incorporate more Jewish things into our household, like weekly Shabbat celebrations, and I am hoping that Honeymoon Israel will encourage us to explore a type of Judaism that is most comfortable for us.

We loved the trip, saw tremendously value in it. We covered this widely in other surveys as well as this one.

I?m not sure why question 42 is appropriate?
I personally do not see its relevance in this survey.
Israel_text:
This is is where I feel most disconnected with the Jewish community. It doesn?t matter that I have kids with Sheena, and that we raised them In a liberal Jewish way. If I do not convert in a specific way, I will never be considered or fully accepted by the state not could be a citizen. This is were I have a harder time understanding the entanglement between state and religion. 
I understand it being difficult to integrate, but in some cases it?s almost impossible. 
If someone is born Jewish, but is not religious at all, he is Jewish and could make Aliyah (with obvious reason) 
However, 
Me being willing to convert (reform) would never be fully recognized, unless I did so the orthodox way being extremely difficult, even more so in my position.
Why, simply because I am a very spiritual person, but not religious by any means. Whether Judaism or any other faith including Christianity..... spirituality, traditions and culture is much more important to me than religion.
Children: No, but we hope to have children in the future
Powerful:
For us, it was a very different trip than for others and took a very different turn than we expected as of day 1. 
The first day we got to Jerusalem, we received a phone call telling us that Sheena?s bubby passed away. Sheena?s grandmother was a joli ost survivor and  lived in Israel where Sheena?s mother was born. She  always regretted leaving and coming to Canada and wanted to make her way back to Israel one day. She loved this country very much. 
We were quickly faced with the decision to stay or leave and after speaking with the family, Sheena decided for us to stay. It?s as if this trip took a whole new meaning for us as her grandmother almost chose to leave the very moment Sheena was in Israel. We decided to view this as a sign that she was with us and this was her way of saying goodbye. We now felt the need to fully embrace the trip and soak in as much of the culture as we could to pay homage and live it for her. 
With technology these days we actually attended her service via live connection and were able to assist while in the country she loved. Overall it was very difficult time, but also made it special in it own way.

Homelife_text: That is difficult for me to answer at this time because I'm not entirely clear on the accepted definition of Jewish home life.  My partner, who is Jewish, grew up with a Jewish father and a Catholic mother, so his household incorporated both faiths, with a heavier leaning towards Reformed Judaism due to his father's influence.  What I have witnessed is that his family will participate in the major Jewish holidays, but they do not regularly have Shabbat or attend temple.
ChildRaise: I am undecided on how to raise our children with respect to Judaism and the Jewish family.  Presently, I think I am very comfortable with honoring the traditions of holidays in our home and even going to temple on occasion (similar to how my partner interacts with his faith now), but my primary concern is understanding that our children will not only be in an interfaith family, but also interracial.  As a black woman, my Christian identity is also important to me; to that end, I am also having my own internal conflict with the Catholic church given the latest unrest, so I am quite torn as to how to proceed in my own faith life, let own with my future children's.
OtherText: I would be interested in some private conversation time with my partner and the rabbi as we embark on marriage together and try to sort out some relationship challenges we have had along the way.
Israel_text: As a Catholic and a black/biracial woman, the realm of what happens in Israel is totally outside of my regular day-to-day, so I will say that I am fairly ignorant of the major issues that exist (but definitely interested in getting educated!)

ChildRaise: It is important for me to give my child a solid grounding in religion, as I think it gives direction and promotes empathy and community. While I personally was raised Catholic and converted, I plan to raise my children in a home that attends a synagogue and is a part of that community. As my parents are Catholic and I am an only child again after the passing of my younger brother, my children will be also exposed to Christian holidays and will be able to celebrate these without reservation with my family. I want my children to understand that there are many ways of viewing the world, and that it is OK to question and also to celebrate diversity. We will celebrate Jewish holidays, participate in Hebrew school teachings, and embrace the ethnic customs in which my husband was raised. I want my children to be happy, open-minded, and well educated within the context of their Jewish faith (i.e. understanding Hebrew, bar/bat mitzvahed, fluency in related customs and traditions).

Homelife_text: Since we are now having a baby, the conversations about how we would describe a Jewish home life has been more and more serious and present. Not that before we were not having this conversation, but I think having a Jewish home life as a family has taken a big part of planning our way to educate our daughter. We have never been very religious and though I believe in God, my husband believes more in something bigger than us that he doesn't call God (I've come to learn that this is very common among Jewish people). Our Jewish home life would have more communication on Jewish tradition, holidays and formal events. We usually go to Shabbat services on Friday and we would like to continue doing that. After Shabbat we always pick a restaurant (it is the day where we actually eat outside in a way to make it different than the rest) to have dinner. We already observe the High Holidays and we will keep doing that, but we also want to make our friends part of this as well.
ChildRaise: To be honest, I think here I'm more lost. I was not raised Jewish, so my knowledge in terms of Jewish education I don't have much information or know much of how we should do it and what are the steps. I want for her to go to summer camps, day school, synagogue. We would read books about it together, I would love to learn Hebrew so I can help her learn as well. I want to know more the history about Israel (that is why I read more books about it), the history behind why we observe certain holidays (so that I can explain our daughter when the time comes and she doesn't just think we observe them because we have to), I would like to have an open communication regarding religion and culture and also, make sure our daughter knows both of our upbringings and knows why we both chose to raise a Jewish family.
OtherText: We would love to be part of this trip, we think that sharing this with other couples would make us have a better connection to the group and the culture/religion and bring friends home that share similar values. But, if this is not a possibility in the next few years, we will make sure to visit Israel as a couple and then take our daughter with us.
Israel_text: I have been learning more about Israel. To be honest it was not in my radar for a long time. That is why I don't feel very confident yet speaking about Israel with other people, because I feel I'm still an amateur and it's such a sensitive topic. I do understand politics in Israel a little more now and I understand what people is talking about when they do. I feel more and more connected to Israel in an emotional level, but I think that having an outside opinion of Israel makes me not have a stronger relationship with Israel and Israelis (especially because I don't know any Israelis and have met some during my trips in South America but haven't built solid friendships with them).

Powerful: There really were so many... There was one night in Jerusalem when, after an amazing dinner at Mona, Jon and I went back to the Western Wall. It was around 10 or 11pm and there were hundreds of ultra-orthodox men there watching a "star" rabbi give a kind of concert. It was just electric. We took it all in and roamed around the Old City until midnight, then took a long, windy walk back to the hotel. These dinners/walks just us were really important. Other couples did big dinners with one another but we felt like we were getting a lot of that during the day and on the nights we were all together. Those "date nights" we had in Jerusalem and Tel Aviv were really great and really important moments for us, not only as a couple but to really unpack the things we saw or thought about that day.

Experiencing the Holocaust museum and hearing the personal story of our guide Ron were absolutely, whole-body gut wrenching. Being able to put together that history with the content we learned in the geopolitical lecture/conversations was really meaningful. I do wish, however, that there was actual space and time to debrief after the visit to the museum as it was an incredibly moving experience. 
Also loved hearing from local Palestinians about their life experiences, wishes and hopes for the future of humankind and its ability to connect through shared humanity rather than fight over land and ideology. I do wish that we could have had more time with them, more programming on the Palestinian perspective and experiences.

Powerful: Hearing Avraham Infeld speak was my most powerful moment. It was exactly what I needed to hear at the right time. Here?s why- I converted to Judaism about three years before this trip. I?m proud that I did, it is not something I hide. But I always lead off with ?I converted? and I?m not sure why. The night before we heard Mr. Infeld speak, I ended up telling a woman in a shop I converted. She was not at all happy about it. It got me thinking why I say that. Hearing Mr. Infeld speak about Judaism resonated with me because he said you don?t convert, you are adopted. If you convert, it is out of Judaism. I thought about that. And it made sense. For three years, I had been saying I converted but in actuality, I was adopted by the most wonderful faith and family. It all made sense, three years later, in Israel, at 8 in the morning. This was exactly where I needed to be, and exactly what I needed to hear.

OtherText:
My husband and I are very discouraged about this program now.  We feel that we were mislead with information about the program all together.  The website shares minimal information and then when you attend the interview it is made clear that they are more focused on looking for EXTREMELY diverse couples not just interested in Judaism.  It wasn't inclusive or welcoming.  With everything shared we felt more and more out of place.  As each additional couple entered the waiting room, they were more diverse.  We kept wondering why all of this wasn't more available on the website as we researched prior to the interview.  The interview was uncomfortably invasive and the interviewers will do anything to get the most personal of details out of you.  
We thought the program was mostly for interfaith couples and we were wrong about that too.  We applied looking for support from Honeymoon Israel's community and we have yet to receive any.  Our original interest for the program peaked as we saw this as an opportunity to join a Jewish community that was more our speed over a synagogue.  We wanted to meet other couples that are in the same stages of life as us so we can support each other.  We were seeking out Jewish organizations to attend, around our area, to begin learning as a couple before having our own children. By the end of the process we felt we were too average and for that we were not accepted. 
For future applicants, it would help if the expectations were made more clear.  What is the program looking for? What is the purpose of each part of the application process?  Who should apply vs who shouldn't?  Did I have too much past experience with Jewish programs which prevented my husband and I from being welcomed to Honeymoon Israel?I guess we'll never know.

Homelife_text: We definitely want kids. I'd love for them to have more of a groundedness and sense of belonging than I had, growing up. Celebrating holidays, shabbat, etc... would go a long way in that direction.
ChildRaise:
I sort of touched on this in the previous question. I'd love for my kids do be connected to their culture and history. It's been scary seeing the brazen antisemitism that's been popping up seemingly everywhere. As someone who still has living relatives who survived the Holocaust, the degree to which history has already been forgotten terrifies me. It feels important for Jews to care about their Jewishness as much as nationalists and nazis seem to.

Also, as a gay couple who will likely adopt, we need to work extra hard to build a foundation and center for our non traditional family. The paradigm hasn't really been written for what that's supposed to look like. I'd love to figure out ways to incorporate Jewish traditions as a means of giving our family roots and branches.

Powerful:
Specifically, the experiences that are still with me include the visit to Yad Vashem, both in terms of the visit itself ? which resonated deeply because much of my family experienced the Holocaust first hand ? and the level of support and comfort I felt from the group, when I COULD NOT STOP CRYING. Visiting the Old City (especially at night) stands out, as well. As does the day we explored the Israeli/Palestinian conflict.

More generally, the level of connectedness I found with the group was surpassed my expectations. I am grateful beyond words that I met many of these people who shared parts of themselves and have since become dear friends.

Also, Tel Aviv was awesome AF.

Homelife_text: Jewish home life means not forgetting what will always be a part of him, and by the extension of him, us. It means celebrating Jewish holidays especially with the community we have built/been blessed with.
ChildRaise: If we have children, I would want us to raise them as religiously as we are ourselves, which admittedly isn't very religious, but definitely more religious now than before the trip. We would want them to celebrate Jewish holidays as we do and grow up in the community we have made with our new friends. But I don't think it is right to force them to practice a religion they don't believe in, whether it's Judaism or any other religion. I want them to grow up with the tools to make that kind of decision for themselves eventually, including the hopefully positive experience they will have with us and Judaism as a child.
Israel_text: By nature of having gone to Israel and having an amazing experience, I already feel emotionally connected to this place on earth. Though I know 10x more about Israel and its history and culture than I did before the trip, you can only learn so much in 10 days so I don't yet feel confident speaking to other about it, but I pay more attention to the news now so I am confident that I will eventually have enough of an understanding of it that I can talk to other about it.

Powerful: Visiting Yad Vashem was particularly powerful. I have been to several holocaust museums in several cities, but sharing the experience with 40+ other people with varying religions, sexualities, races, and upbringings and coming together to for this visceral experience was very very powerful to me.
LifeEvent: Experiencing a loss; Experiencing a health challenge
Adjective_text: much more comfortable now than before. I will never feel 100% comfortable as I am not Jewish and will never have the relationship with Judaism as if I was born and raised Jewish. But I feel confident in doing Jewish things with my partner and my new HMI community. I once felt way out of place, and now I don't. And as I continue to do Jewish things, the more comfortable I feel and the more knowledgeable of the culture and religion I become. And I feel confident when talking to people outside of my HMI family now that I truly feel a part of the community.
HMIDiff: They are similar in that we are mostly in the same age range, similar paths of life, liberal, respectful, otherwise I wouldn't be friends with them. But these relationships are different in that I shared something so specific with my HMI friends that I will take with me until the day I die. It's true, I may or may not have had very specific bonds with other non-HMI friends, but the HMI bond feels particularly special and I am so excited to see how our new friendships evolve and bring us closer together.

Homelife_text: Jewish home life for me, is having my family understand how the teachings of Judaism are woven into each aspect of our life. I would like for my children to have a bar/bat mitvah and I love celebrating the holidays, so expect to do so in my home.

ChildRaise:
This is something my husband I talked about really early in our relationship. We're an interfaith home and we've decided we're going to treat our children as adults from the get go. They have Jewish and Christian heritage and we will expose them to both. Its important to me that they never feel that one is "mom's way" or "dad's way." To help with that we've both put significant effort in understanding both religions and cultures. Ironically, I'm Christian and it's very important to me we send our children to Hebrew school, perhaps even more so than it is to my husband.

We plan on celebrating all holidays and remaining involved in Jewish organizations we're passionate about. Prior to HMI we were already involved with the ADL. I hope our children will share our passions but they are free to choose their own path. 

Above all else, we want an inclusive welcoming household where both traditions are valued, celebrated, and respected.

Powerful:
The most powerful moment for me personally was probably the Tsfat experience with the Kabbalah artist. I'd never appreciated that Judaism can be a vehicle for spirituality--I'd always seen it as a stern tradition of rules and order, which I struggled to connect with emotionally. 

The most powerful experiences for us as a couple were the periods of free time spent getting to know other HMI couples. These moments gave us an opportunity to digest the programming, and to discuss the different ways that the BIG questions affected our lives. We learned a lot about what was important to us/what we were searching for by hearing others articulate it. And since coming back, that shared experience has facilitated a strong bond.

I love the community and ritual aspects, and the opportunity to inquire about a deeper sense of spirituality, but dislike the intonation of exclusivity that "Jewish things" denotes.

OtherText: Question 36 - I find this hard to answer because there is such variety in people and in Jewish people. I think I'm like most Jewish people I come across working in Entertainment but I live close to Pico-Robinson/the Orthodox community and I don't think my Jewish life reflects theirs at all, not even a little. I am Jewish by heritage but not religion. Most people in the HMI group are like me but some are not, so it's hard to answer that with just one response. Thank you so much again to the wonderful HMI team and Jen. We had a great experience and I've loved meeting everyone and hope to continue these friendships.

Homelife_text: I'd like to carry with me certain traditions and cultures that shaped my ancestors and grandparents so I can also honor their struggles by keeping Judaism alive. I'm not religious, I'm practically atheist, as I often call myself a "Humanist" but I have a love for my Jewish culture.

Israel_text: I have a strong need and care to help keep Israel safe and represented fairly to the eyes of the world. I find myself very emotional when I see that Israel is displayed in unfair terms using obscene words like "apartheid" to describe it. I can't go on twitter. How ppl think Israel exists in some kind of bubble and that they don't have hostile neighbors on all sided. How the world doesn't take this into account when judging things that happen. Especially because my dad escaped from Iraq to Israel, I know that many middle-eastern Jews were displaced. Something that is too often left out of the conversation. Like only Jews from Europe invaded the land. That frustrates me. I'm a democrat and progressive person who is very anti-Trump. I feel a great need to represent the democratic, progressive community that stands with Israel and helps ppl to understand their struggles. I think more Jews turning to Trump defeats the purpose of helping Israel, especially in the long run. We need to make the world understand Israel and we won't do so by friending the current "devil".  Ppl can be critical of Israel but I fear the growth of things like BDS and I see how much havoc is wreaked by groups like Jewish Voices for Peace. It broke my heart when I learned that black lives matter aligned with them and that Julia Salazar a pro bds person will be a senator. We need ppl on the left to explain the complex issues so that propaganda doesn't win. I feel connected to the land and I see how most Jewish Americans who have no connection to it, are more okay to throw Israel under the bus. And there are those who went on things like birthright and told Israel is perfect. They then grow skeptical and throw the baby out with the bathwater. They need to be taught to understand why Israel is how it is.

He was fine to have a Rabbi marry us.  I would like to figure out how we can have a Jewish-ish home and a celebration of Jewish things when we have a child that doesn't interfere with our shared agnostic beliefs.

Homelife_text: For me - I feel Jewish much more so as a culture/ethnicity - as who I am. As religion goes, there are parts of it that are about a Jewish way of life that I connect to and appreciate - like Shabbat, for instance. Religiously, I'm a Humanist and don't have much desire to become more religious.
ChildRaise: I really want our child to know her roots and where she comes from and the tribe she's a part of. I'd like her to learn about her culture without implementing too much of the religious context onto her. I'd like her to learn about the stories, the beauty, the interpretations but I don't want her to feel like this is the end all she needs to believe. I think it would be nice for her to learn Hebrew too. I'd like to celebrate Shabbat - perhaps on a monthly or biweekly basis. I'm undecided as to if I think she should have a Bat Mitzvah but I'd like her to do something that year that represents it, if not a literal Bat Mitzvah.

Powerful: I found it very powerful to be in a true safe space with new friends as we openly explored and talked about things that are important to me but that I don't always feel comfortable or safe talking about. For me, my connection to Israel is powerful and the black and white villainization of the Israel in my own progressive circles has be been rather frightening to watch. I love that HMI is run in a liberal, free thinking and kind way and I love how popular it has become. Because of this, it's at the brink of something really special - showing the more nuanced truth behind Israel and the many reasons to love it. I've voiced this in prior surveys but my one concern is that HMI continues to be aware of the tremendous growth of anti-zionism, especially in Jewish circles. I actually felt a pressure in my group to explain a lot of Israel's struggle that many in my group didn't understand. I think that it HMI is going to continue East Jerusalem tours than it is equally important that the groups hear from Israeli soldiers and victims of terrorist bombs. I'm most fearful of the growing anti-zionism that's extremely linked to anti-semitism and I hope that HMI uses the good work they're doing to spread love in this area.

Homelife_text: I would like for my family to grow up with the beautiful customs and traditions of Judaism, just as I did. My husband is not religious and I do not expect that he will convert, but I wish for our family to embrace Judaism and to carry its traditions forward, and for my children to grow up with Sunday school, Bat/Bar Mitzvahs, and high holiday services - and for them to have a great network of Jewish friends. I also wish for my husband and I to build connections in the Jewish community and for much of our social justice and volunteer activities to include connections to the LA Jewish community. Hopefully - if we have the opportunity to attend Honeymoon Israel someday - that this community of friends will be a key part of building this foundation and helping us to achieve and maintain this level of engagement and connections in a meaningful way.
ChildRaise: As outlined above, we are planning to raise our children Jewish, in an interfaith family as my husband does not plan to convert. While we have generally agreed upon this principle, my husband has not been fortunate to experience more daily Jewish traditions outside of the major holidays, and I seek to offer opportunities for us to experience these traditions and excursions together to help him to learn and appreciate these opportunities as I have learned over the years. I would love for our children to be raised with Judaism as their religious foundation, while being exposed to many other traditions, cultures and religions to enhance their respect for diversity and empathy for others. I also wish for Judaism and Tikkun Olam to help forge the foundation of our family's focus on social justice and philanthropy, with a key focus on the LA and Southern California communities. Community, education, and social justice are three areas that are of critical importance to me and how I foresee Judaism playing a role in how we raise our children and define our family.
OtherText:
While all of these items are very important to us, the current foundations of connections that we have within the Jewish community in LA are limiting our ability to prioritize and expand upon these desires and making them into more firm commitments in our life. We are very much looking for that opportunity and see our focus on the LA Jewish community and our desire to invest and contribute to LA as a means for how we would contribute to Honeymoon Israel - both while on the trip and upon returning.

This is a very thoughtful and comprehensive survey and am grateful for the opportunity to submit. While we are very disappointed after having been rejected for the trip for the second time, would welcome more transparency around upcoming trips and the potential for adding any trips to 2019, particularly as we are very engaged with discussions on family planning, and a trip like this would be worth planning around (as much as possible!). Thank you again for the opportunity and we look forward to feedback.
Children: No, but we hope to have children in the future
JewishFam_text: As of now, our family - being just the two of us - is lacking a key connection and lifeline to the Jewish community that I am personally looking for, and that my husband has been very supportive in looking to cultivate, particularly through Honeymoon Israel. We are very keen to participate in this once in a lifetime opportunity to help provide this foundation for building the ideal Jewish home life that I outlined above, and particularly before we start a family, which could be as early as next year. I wish for our personal connections as a couple to grow, and for faith to be a part of the bedrock of the teachings that we will share with our children, which will focus on Judaism though integrate other secular participation in other holidays.
GoalChange: Yes; we had indicated in our second application that we are interested in starting a family soon, and that this trip would be an invaluable opportunity for us to build connections in the Jewish community in LA, and to expand our opportunity to grow as a couple and refine our approach to Judaism as we look to have children in the near future.

Homelife_text: I think since the trip I realized that if I do have children, I really want them to have a Jewish education and upbringing. I didn't realize how important it was to me and my upbringing, and I guess I didn't realize exactly how Jewishly I was raised until the trip. If we do not have children, I feel I do want a "more" Jewish home. Our lives are very busy, but I am hopeful that we can take an Intro to Judaism class together, that we can take time out to celebrate Shabbat, or that we can delve a little bit more deeply into the parts of Judaism that are meaningful for me. Though I can't say I have figured out how exactly do do this yet, I do know I would like more Judaism in my life. I can't say I know exactly what my ideal "Jewish home life" looks like, but I can say I have enjoyed celebrating Shabbat with my new friends from HMI, and that I have enjoyed trying to carve some more space for that part of myself.

OtherText:
Question 42: Income varies year by year. 

I am eternally grateful for HMI -- for the experience, for the cohort, and for what it has given me and my partner. I hope many more couples in the future get to experience this and that it strengthens the Jewish community, creates new Jewish community and that it helps mixed faith couples find a way to incorporate Judaism, Jewish identity and other mixed faith couples into their lives as it did for us.

MeaningTrip_08text: Meeting local Israelis. Learning more about the history of the Jewish people. Understanding more about the politics of Israel. Spending spiritual moments like Shabbat by the beach and prayers at the Western Wall. Exposing my partner to Jewish tradition.
Powerful: There we so many powerful experiences in Israel, culminating with Avram Infeld's lecture about Judaism as a people rather than a religion. I think that was a powerful moment for myself and my partner as it sort of brought the whole trip full circle. From seeing the relics of the Jewish people past at the Israel Museum, to feeling the presence of the generations of Jews before me at the Western Wall, to understanding the diaspora, and understanding the presence of Israel in a new light, I think the trip really made me reconnect with my Jewish identity and what being Jewish means to me. I think it helped my partner understand more completely what it is to be sharing a life with a Jewish woman and making Judaism a part of his life. Of course besides our own powerful experiences as a couple, we had many powerful experiences and discussions as a group that really bonded us closely from experiencing Yad Vashem together, to dinner gatherings and debates, there were countless moments that were moving and powerful for the group as a whole.
HMIDiff: I have connected more with my new HMI friends than many of my other friends from  other aspects of my life. I can honestly say HMI did an incredible job of finding like minded people, and I can think of at least 6 couples who I am so incredibly glad to have met and now have become really important friends in my life. I have found myself having deeper conversations with them, and becoming really close to them quite quickly, and it's been really nice to have friends that are couples that my partner and I met together and have similar interests to. I was shocked at how amazing of a group HMI put together of people with really similar personalities, interests and depth. I am so grateful to have them and am hopeful that we will continue not only an amazing lifelong friendship, but truly building this Jewish community I know some of us are really hoping to create.
HMIBarrier_text: I think it's time consuming for everyone with extremely busy jobs to plan things or find things like volunteer opportunities, book clubs and educational things. We've been able to maintain getting together with some close friends we've made (which we absolutely love!) and doing our monthly Shabbats, but are hoping to incorporate some more Jewish-related experiences into the mix. I know our planning committee had some great ideas, but putting them into action is the next step.

Homelife_text: Celebrating traditions and holidays and creating a community of like minded faith and values.  The recurring traditions are an important part of that but I believe that you shouldn't be bound by traditions so much as inspired by them.  Culturally, among all religions, "tradition" often becomes a hard rule to follow vs an desired experience of inspiration.  And when that happens, it can lose meaning.  I think the closer you are to a community, which I hope to gain from this, the more you can develop that inspiration.  It's easy to consider a "Jewish home life" as following a set of rules based in tradition, but I'd like to develop a life of traditions based on inspiration.
ExpectPostTrip_08text: I hope to bring back a sense of connection not just to Judaism but to my family's faith, Christianity, and how the two intersect.
ChildRaise: In this instance, I believe that it's more important for my partner to raise possible children in the Jewish faith than it is for me to raise them in the Christian faith.  Having said that, I wouldn't want to abdicate the position that Christianity might play in their upbringing.  Again, I would prefer that they be exposed to both, maybe even a third, to understand the traditions that come with each, participate in those, and then discuss and help them grow to make their own choice.  The last thing I think either of us want is to "make" our kids go to church or temple every Sunday because we feel like they "have" to.  I don't think either one of us would want that for our children.
OtherText: Something that might not come up  overtly, because of the nature of the organization sponsoring this trip, is how this visit might inform and inspire my own connection to the Christian faith.  That has been lacking in my adulthood and I'm hoping a trip like this, focusing on the religious connections of my partner, might inspire my own re-exploration of the faith I was raised in and look for value there as well.  Not the primary focus of this experience for me, but absolutely something I am open to.
Israel_text: I have always understood the connection to Israel as it relates to both Judaism and Christianity.  I understand to a degree to differing ideologies of religions in the country now and how those differences have led to extreme cases of conflict.  I have never thought of this as a deterrent to visit, but perhaps it's never seemed as flashy a place to earmark as a vacation experience, hence my answer to it being on my radar.  However the HMI context feels so right to me to visit Israel.  I am so excited to see the sights while also letting the significance of the country sink in and explore our relationship to the Jewish faith as a result.
Children: No, but we hope to have children in the future
JewishFam_text: My partner and I are interfaith, he was raised Jewish and I was raised Christian.  We both had strong upbringings based in tradition, as defined above, that became obligations.  As adults we have developed our own life outside of those obligations while respecting each other when we choose to recognize our faith, and sometimes participate in that with each other and sometimes not.
ExpectTrip_8text: Learning about myself and how I respond in a situation like this.
GoalChange: Not really.  I'm excited to learn and grow as a couple and as an individual.

FutChildReligion_text: I would love to raise my children to understand and appreciate the good things from multiple religions and then encourage them to choose what inspires them most as they grow.

Homelife_text: I was raised Christian and have no intention of converting to Judaism.  I am happy to explore the aspects of Judaism that are relevant to my partner, but it is not a priority for me personally.  If anything, what is important for me is that members of my family explore all religions equally and explore what resonates with them the most.
ChildRaise: It's important for me that we raise any children we have to understand the pillars of both Judaism and Christianity as well as any other religions that resonate with us.  I have always wanted to explore Buddhism for example.  I think raising a family to believe one thing and having that thing be absolute inherently implies that all who don't believe that are wrong and excluded.  And that is a philosophy I will never subscribe to.
OtherText: I went into this trip expecting there to be a call to action to join the Jewish community.  I was hesitant about the trip for that reason.  I was very pleasantly surprised that the trip did not feel that way at all.  While I have leveled criticism in other surveys about the trip being too much a singular vision of the Jewish experience versus a method in which to help rationalize the different religious views inherent in interfaith couples, I did not feel obligated or expected to convert by the end of the trip.  With the exception of the last speaker, no one involved pressured me one way or the other, which I really appreciated.  Since returning from the trip, though, the HMI Organization has not been involved at all in any of the connections I have maintained.  And it seems to only be interested in how inspired I was by the trip to convert to Judaism or live as much of a Jewish life as possible.  And that's disappointing.  But I choose to remember the trip for the amazing experience that it was and take from it what I thought was the intention, rather than the recruitment tool that it appears to have been all along.
Israel_text: Nothing else to say really.  I do understand it more, which I appreciate.

ChildReligion_text: I can't say that no other religion will play a role.
Powerful: The trip was wonderful.  It was also overwhelming.  It took a while to decompress and take stock of what I gained from it after I was back.  In hindsight, the big takeaway for me was meeting the other couples.  The shred experience of HMI connected us in a way that is hard to explain.  It's impossible to maintain meaningful contact with everyone, but 5-6 couples emerged through shared interest and likability that have been integral to my life since.
Adjective_text: I feel it is up to my partner and what is important to him.  Nothing we have done together has spoken to me personally or made me feel like I want to explore the religion further.   What they have done is shed light onto my partner and what drives him.  There is great value in that I will continue to do those things to connect with him.  But I would not seek these out on my own, and frankly, don't feel welcome to without him.
HMIDiff: The HMI Friends started off with the trip.  The first couple of months, these friendships revolved around discussing the trip and returning to the "real world" and what that meant.  Slowly, similar interests emerged and those that became true friends are now just that; friends.  Integrating friendship circles now becomes no greater a challenge than integrating other friendships circles (ie friends from school with friends from work).  It's all just a matter of opportunity.
HMIBarrier_text: There is nothing really preventing me from making time to get together with couples other than regular life things that existed long before the trip.  Going on the trip did not magically allot me more social time when I got back or less responsibilities in life.

OtherText: Honeymoon Israel was an incredible experience. But I am grateful for the opportunity to meet new friends and see Israel and become more knowledgeable about the issues.

OtherText: As someone without a Jewish connection through friends or family (at least on my side of the aisle), I look for any opportunity to make a connection so that I can continue to learn.  The biggest draw for me to this is the opportunity to have a network of friends that are Jewish that we can discuss together what that means to them.  No one has ever made me feel like an outsider in any of the events I have attended with my partner, but I would love to make some real friends and feel a stronger connection to the Jewish community.

As such, I think it is best to have a strong connection to one religion, and after discussing with my soon-to-be-wife, that will be Judaism for us.  The more I learn, the better I feel about this decision and feel a need to include my upbringing simply to repeat my history for my children.  Being a Jewish family will provide all I want for my kids.

Homelife_text: In our home we like to honor our Jewish heritage by having mezuzahs on our front door and on the doors to the bedrooms, having art in our home from Jewish and Israeli artists, and displaying Judaica including our menorahs, shabbat candles, kiddish cups, and challah platter.
ChildRaise: We are members of a local synagogue so we bring our kids to tot services when they're offered and we will be sending them to religious school when they are old enough. We also celebrate many of the Jewish holidays at home or with family such as Hanukkah, Passover, and Purim. We are members of the PJ Library which has been very helpful in introducing our daughter to Jewish culture and tradition in an age appropriate age. She is 2 1/2 at the moment and our son is less than 2 months so he will be included soon as well.
Israel_text: I have never visited Israel, although it is a dream of mine. There is a lot of disagreement in what people say about Israeli politics and since I don't have first hand information it is hard for me to make my own opinions. I have a few very close friends who are Israeli, but that is not enough to really form an opinion on the country as a whole.
Children: Yes
JewishFam_text: We both identify as Jewish, but my dad was not Jewish so growing up when I'd go to his house in the winter we would get a Christmas tree. Jeff and I have chosen to incorporate that tradition in our home except we just call it a holiday tree and we do not decorate it with anything overtly Christmasy. Instead we decorate it with ornaments of animals, pictures of family, and purple and blue lights because those are our favorite colors. We also go to events like egg hunts because they are fun activities for children. We don't feel like our kids should miss out on fun things even though they are technically Christian holidays. As we see it, most people we know aren't religious at all but still engage in those traditions so there is no harm in letting our kids experience them too.
GoalChange: When we first applied for Honeymoon Israel I was pregnant with our second child and he was born in September. Unfortunately because of these life events we probably won't be applying for another Honeymoon Israel trip.

ChildRaise: Both of our children had naming ceremonies at our temple and we bring them to Tot-shabbats and other young children related events (high holiday services, etc). I would like for them to go to a jewish summer camp as I did growing up, whether it be day or sleep away. We look forward to having them attend religious school weekly when they are old enough and to be bar and bat mitzvah'd. We want them to feel a part of a community of other Jews and learn about the importance of service to others in need (bringing food to someone sick, helping build homes for the homeless, collecting clothes, making local parks look beautiful by picking up trash. These are just a few of the things I hope they can find meaning in.

It is important for her to raise our daughter in a way that helps her understand and appreciate her cultural and ethnic background as she grows up, and give her the tools, information and ability to assess how she will want to make all things jewish part of her life in the future. While i am completely disenfranchised from the catholic church for many reasons, i also share my cultural heritage with our daughter, which includes traditions originally stemming from religious rites (think christmas). It is my hope that we as a family will blend the best of both worlds in our home, and that our daughter won't let others define what she is or is not, but domit herself.

Homelife_text: In our family, Jewish home life is very connected/related to traditions and family, since we are not religious people. Understanding where it comes from, how it helps define our family and "making it work" for us in our own way rather than adhering to dogmas.
ChildRaise: We are raising our daughter Jewish; while I was raised catholic, I am not a religious person at all but I do understand that there are elements other than religion that define Judaism (family, history, tradition, etc.), which is why I am OK with giving our daughter the opportunity to learn about all of that, and eventually decide by herself if (and/or how) she wants to be less/equally or more involved with Judaism. I also think that modern Judaism will be much more mixed (i.e. more interfaith couples) and open to other traditions and backgrounds, or will otherwise struggle to retain a base, and I want our daughter to have that type of  "flexibility" and acceptance of other cultures hardwired in her core.
OtherText: It has been over 3 months since we returned home from our trip to Israel, and the impact is enduring. It was an experience I won't forget and I am glad and grateful we had the opportunity to go with HMI. I am also happy that we have managed to stay in touch with a few more couples, and that, in a sense, we are part of the HMI family.
Israel_text: I feel that I can better advocate for Israel when I'm talking to people who are always critical of the country, or buy into the constant mainstream leftist Israel = evil and Palestine = victims BS. I lie having seen things by myself.

Powerful: The visit to Jerusalem was particularly powerful in many aspects, since it provide us with the opportunity to get more familiar with the issues that define Judaism, both in the past and today. Adjective_text: Well, considering I am not Jewish, the dominating feeling I have is "Included". Everyone has been very welcoming and accepting, which for me is key.

Homelife_text: Shabbat, discussing Jewish history with our kids, sending our kids to Hebrew school, instilling our shared values in their daily lives (tikkun olam, tzedakah, being kind to one another)
ChildRaise:
We are raising our kids Jewish, and this is something we've talked about since day one (and Max included it in his vows!) 
Raising Jewish children is incredibly important to me - from teaching them Jewish history, to taking them to Hebrew school, and celebrating their bar/bat Mitzvahs, I can't wait to teach them about their faith. It's also important to me that our children experience the traditions of Max's family as I think part of what has made my Jewish identity so strong is the exposure I've always had to other faiths and religions. 
What I love about being Jewish is that it means something different to each person - every Jewish person in my life experiences Judiaism in a different way and its important to me to let my kids define their own Jewish experience. I remember growing up, my Dad made it very clear to my sister and I that it was important to pass along our Jewish identity because we couldn't let it end with us. I feel a great pride and responsibility to make sure our faith gets passed down from generation to generation.

OtherText: Lately, after the shootings in pittsburgh; I have been thinking a lot about what it's going to mean when I bring Jewish children into this world. Growing up catholic, I never really experienced any negative acts based on my faith and never had to worry about being shot based on my ethnicity or religion. However, now that I have married into a Jewish family I am more aware of these kinds of hate acts or negative opinions regarding Judaism. And since these shootings, I am genuinely scared thinking about my children, who will be jewish, being bullied or harmed over something that I cannot control. We are several years away from having kids, but I would be interested to know how others are dealing with this fear or if this is even a fear for others.

Powerful:
One moment I will never forget was all of the women going to the women's side of the Kotel. We had a moment away from our partners where I think we all recognized that we'll have our own experience with Judaism (or spirituality or whatever) that maybe our partners can not understand. I don't think there was a single dry eye and even though no one really said anything, we shared something. It made me feel closer to this group.

Lighting the Hanukkah candles with everyone every night was another important, unforgettable experience. Each night it felt more important and bigger and by the last night of Hanukkah I was so used to having these new friends around me that when we lit the candles (at home) the difference was so stark it highlighted how amazing the community we'd formed had become in just a week.

Israel_text: I try to keep regularly updated on broad israeli and middle eastern geo-politics, though I avoid local politics in the region. I am very pro-Israel and believe it has a right to exist and that it serves a tremendous purpose to inspire the jewish community globally (+ is a terrific ally in the region for he US). I primarily struggle with the issue of settlements and it is frustrating not feeling like Israel is always taking the high road. While I recognize that the society and education system in Gaza/West Bank propagates intolerance toward Israel, I am also sympathetic to young people that are born into that world and don't know any differently. I can understand why those without an understanding of Israel and the jewish people's history would take the side of "occupied" persons and support the BDS movement. Still, I don't think BDS is a productive solution to the problem and it's frustrating how one-sided media coverage of the conflict is against Israel.
