Homelife_text: I am very much still exploring my personal opinions on this topic, but this trip has reawakened (or awakened) me to my Jewish identity and heritage, especially my relationship with my mother and her family's traditions.  It is very important to me to continue to practice the traditions she and I have shared since I was a child, perhaps especially because my father and my two half-brothers are not Jewish, so the traditions were very much between my mother and I.  I have struggled at times to win Sara's full buy-in of the new and old traditions I would like to build into our lives, including our new Shabbat ritual of turning off technology, lighting candles, and spending some quality time together each Friday night, as well as my tradition of lighting the Hanukkah menorah with my mom each night.  All that said, that's pretty much the extent of the role I envision my Judaism playing in our home life.  I don't feel much of a need to go any deeper into the Jewish community, nor explore Judaism from a religious standpoint, or any of that.
ChildRaise: What I think is important in terms of my future children's relationship with Judaism is the same way I think about my own relationship with it: the ideology matters very little (to me), but feeling a personal connection to my family history and to my mother is very important to me, and it will be important to me to instill at least a knowledge of that family heritage to he/she/them.
OtherText: As I said earlier, this trip was truly the trip of a lifetime for me, and I hope that statement means perhaps a little bit more given the degree of detachment I had personally felt from Judaism and Israel before getting involved in this trip.  The trip was so incredibly fun and meaningful that returning to normal life has been somewhat tricky.  I am enormously grateful to have had the opportunity to go on this trip and be welcomed into the HMI community, and I want to thank everyone that works hard to give people like me an opportunity to experience it.
Israel_text: One thing that really would have made an impact, I think, is creating some sort of structured time for us to meet and interact with more actual Israelis.  Koren is the lone friend of mine that lives in Israel, which is great - now I have one!  But my connection to the land and the state and the people would be so much deeper if I had other people I had met.
Children: No, but we hope to have children in the future
Powerful: The most powerful experiences were those that involved other couples.  The first few that come to mind are going to Yad Vashem; running through the torrential rain in Tel Aviv from the bar to our hotel, and then trying to order food only to get Domino's; group-singing '90s pop hits on the bus back from the Hanukkah party; collectively joking about our superiority to the Chicago group.  The list goes on.  For me personally, the trip was truly once in a lifetime in several respects: an incredible experience in and of itself, with a ton of learning and bonding with new friends, and being in a magical place for the first time; an awakening for me to my Jewish heritage, and my linkage to that place and those people; the beginning of a seemingly bottomless fascination, which continues today, with the modern history of the state of Israel.  It actually exceeded my expectations, which were very high.
Adjective_text: Through my own choices, I have not become very involved in the local Jewish community.  That's by design.  It does, however, make me feel like an outsider again, though, at least with our HMI counterparts, many of whom seem to be getting more and more involved with Jewish life.
HMIDiff: Our new HMI friendships are generally vastly deeper than my other friendships.  The shared intense experience was profound.

Homelife_text: I'm really not sure exactly what Jewish home life looks like because I'm not the Jew in our relationship, but I know it is important to my husband that our children be raised to be in touch with their Jewish identity.  I really like the idea of using Judaism as a way to (1) explore shared values and social justice themes with my children; (2) explore spirituality; and (3) connect with my husband's extended family and a wider community.  That being said, I am not Jewish and I am pretty ambivalent about converting because I'm not religious and don't think I even believe in God (hence it seems weird to convert to any religion).  So a major concern for me is how I would be accepted if my children were brought up going to a synagogue and participating in Jewish life; I wouldn't want to feel like an outsider or like I wasn't really part of it. So I want to figure out how I can educate myself and participate short of conversion.  I don't know if this topic will come up at all on the trip, but I would say this is my #1 concern; is there a place among the "chosen people" for some random lady who just happened to marry into it?
ChildRaise: Following the theme of my husband being a secular Jew, the thing he cares most about is that our children attend a Jewish summer camp like he did.  His parents literally met at a Jewish summer camp as counselors, and he attended that same camp.  It's very important to him that our children do the same.  I think we're open to the idea of our kids also attending synagogue school or some other kind of children's programming put on my a synagogue, but only if it was the right fit (progressive, open-minded, etc.)
OtherText: I wish I had more time to prepare and familiarize myself with some Jewish traditions because I feel there's a lot I don't know and I've never been super comfortable in religious settings because I wasn't brought up in a household that was religious.  But I am viewing this trip as just a first step; I want to continue learning when I return, and I'm hoping this will just be a good foundation on which to build so that by the time we start our family we have a better idea of what we want our child's Jewish upbringing to look like.
Israel_text: One of the biggest fights I've ever had with my husband was about Israel and it's conduct vis a vis the Palestinians.  He is very defensive of Israel and it is hard for us to talk about it.  I think being married to him has changed my views somewhat and made me more apt to sympathize with Israelis, but I still find myself extremely conflicted and uncomfortable discussing the politics of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict.  Human rights issues are really important to me, and I find it hard to reconcile some of Israel's policies towards the Palestinians, but I also realize that "Israel" is not one entity; it is made up of diverse people with very different points of view, and I know there are plenty of Israeli Jews who also do not support the settlements and do not support all of the policies of their government (just as I don't support all of my government's policies).

JewishFam_text: I'm not religious so it's not really true to say that we "honor both partners' faith traditions." The truth is that we are both really secular people, and I think we want to just honor each of our backgrounds and families, and that means continuing to celebrate a very secular Christmas as my family has always done and somehow also instilling a Jewish identity in our children and observing Jewish holidays like Passover as my husband's family has always done.  What is tough for me is how to do that without necessarily going all in with organized religion because I don't think either of us is particularly keen on raising our kids in a devout religious household.

OtherText:
We loved the trip and have recommended several other couples to apply. 

HMI missed an opportunity to share a dual-narative perspective. I fear that because of this, many participants are left to CNN and Google to explain the complex issues Israel is has created for itself. Most participants lack the exposure and vernacular to describe _why_ Israel is struggling to maintain peace, and as a result they're unable to talk about it and share the message of HMI.

Koren almost ruined the trip for us. One two occasions I actually packed up my back and intended to leave. He failed to stay organized and was frustrating to work around. On top of it, he has posted offensive and ill-informed articles on his personal facebook account, and de-friended most of us.

JewishFam_text:
I feel like I don't know what "a jewish family" means.  Though most people would probably call our family a "jewish family" and most people would call me a "jew", I feel insecure about those terms and labels.

I also feel like I grew up with some traditions and lack of other traditions (which is also a form of tradition).  I don't quite feel like these are part of our family.  In some sense, I got used to "nothing" and replacing it with "something" feels like a part of my identity is going away.  I don't feel like this feeling/unease/tension is something that I'm able to properly convey to my partner.

Powerful: The story that the man told us in the Palestinian town about his son asking about the sound of the lights (the point of the story is that his son only knew about lights being powered from a generator, which makes noise, and when he was in a jewish school there was no sound, because there's electricity infrastructure from the grid).

Homelife_text: I think the biggest thing would be maintaining values of reformed judiasm and pursuing tikkun olam.  I don't think we necessarily have to practice traditions daily or weekly, but that we would observe shabbat occasionally, and practice some of the big holidays.
ChildRaise: It'll be important for our children to identify as Jewish, and to recognize what that means.  They will be here because their great grandmother went through the Holocaust, and multiple generations have survived persecution.  I think its important they know and understand this history, despite it not necessarily being "my history" (although now it is).  Beyond the history alone, though, the Jewish community is a beautiful thing, and I also want them to feel comfortable in the community and appreciate how fortunate we all are to be a part of it.

HMIDiff: well my friends like me, listen to me, care about what's happening in my life and are supportive, they invite me to fun and interesting things (and vice versa) and involve me in their lives. my HMI cohort is polite, superficially friendly, and that's about it. they do not ask me questions, do not involve me in their conversations or events, do not seem interested in anything I have to say and don't respond to any of my or my husband's posts. so yeah, they are completely different.
HMIBarrier_text: none of these factors really prevent me from getting together with the other HMI couples in my cohort. lack of invitations is the issue. everyone signed up during the trip to do something monthly. we've done one reunion and one passover seder. that's it. i'm not sure what happened to the monthly get-togethers.we also barely had a community manager and then she moved before she could learn all our names so now I guess we don't have one. there was the furry scurry that someone organized but we don't have a dog so we didn't participate. i think there was also an israel day thing but it wasn't event more like someone posting they'd be there and asking if anyone else was going. there may be other things going on but its not on Telegram therefore I don't have the chance to join. Once someone posted about going on a hike, I posted a response about being interested. the reply was something along the lines of "we'll see who else can participate, if the date doesn't work we'll choose another" and then I never saw anything on telegram again. so really its lack of invitations and organization. i suppose I could organize something but i'm not very encouraged by the fact that my posts never get any responses or acknowledgment. I put Telegram on silence so it doesn't notify me when someone posts and it made me feel a lot better to be honest.

One of the components that allowed this authentic relationship-building was the second most powerful experience, the HMI conversations. The structure of these conversations and everyone's willingness to fully engage in them broke down barriers almost immediately (day 2). Hearing other couple's experiences disarmed us and helped to make those connections really quickly, and it also allowed us to continue the conversation outside of the formal structure.

MeaningTrip_08text: Raz, our tour guide was an amazing element of our tour, he really put himself out there and he was well cherished and admired. We appreciated seeing his home and the Gaza border, venturing to East Jerusalem, and exploring all of the complexities and nuance of the state of Israel through scholarly lectures.
Powerful: The most powerful experience I had was our visit to Raz's moshave. That day, we had in-depth conversations about what life is like in his town, add to an art installation that was a message of peace and good-will, and view the border of Gaza complete with all of the security measures in place. The following day, rockets were launched from Gaza, Raz had to leave the tour and take care of his family and neighbors, and we all thought deeply about the conflict with so many people suffering on both sides. It is a complicated tragedy, and my heart felt heavy for all the innocent people whose lives are steeped in this conflict.

It is incumbent upon each of us to bring those elements that are important to us forward in the same way that it is incumbent on the other to embrace them. OtherText: I just want to include a note of appreciation. This was an incredible experience. It was such a long time from when we first attended the info session to when we went on the trip and now it's so hard to believe it's already over! I wish we could go back and do it all again. I'm so appreciative of the opportunity that you provided us to do this. I learned so much - about Israel, about myself, about my wife, about our shared life together - it's truly remarkable. Thank you. Thank you.

MeaningTrip_08text: I just learned so much from the experience. Just saying learning about Israel doesn't quite cut it. It was learning about religious origins - of multiple faiths, culture, food, shared experiences, life in ancient times, etc. It was an incredibly powerful experience in so many ways.
Powerful:
Visiting the Kotel on Friday night. My conservative Christian upbringing taught me that religion was quiet, reserved, controlled and basically wasn't allowed to be fun. It blew me away to get off the bus 300 yards away from the Kotel and we could already hear the singing! And the celebration that we saw was so beautiful and powerful. And that happens every week! It blew me away. And as part of a same sex couple it was wonderful to get to experience the wall together even if the ultra-orthodox would have never approved! :)   

Visiting Memorial Mountain. The Children's Memorial. I can't put that into words. Learning about the Righteous Among The Nations and being thankful that so many had that courage. Hoping that I never have to find out if I am that courageous. 

Walking the Via Dolorosa and bringing the story that I've been told over and over to life. 

Ultimately, I thought the entire experience was more powerful because we had Avraham Infeld's talk that very first morning. For me, framing the entire trip around our shared and different cultures rather than religion completely changed my perspective. It certainly resonated with us both and became a topic of conversation for us. I couldn't think of a better way to begin the trip.

Homelife_text: I?d actually like to address this question as what my ?interfaith? home looks like. I have really tried very hard. I plan the holidays, I have many many Jewish artifacts around our home, I have Shabbat dinners even if just alone with Diego at home when he gets out of work whether it be 6pm or 10pm. I try new Jewish recipes and even try to incorporate his South American culture into it because some of the Jewish traditions in South America are different. I try very hard but I don?t have the same amount of effort in regards to my religion which is fine but I feel like we can?t really have conversations about important topics like baptisms, how we are explaining our religions to children and things I feel are very important. Although our parents are very supportive each side really suggests only what they know which is their religious background.
ExpectPostTrip_08text: Continuing to share our lives together and explore the avenues of our interfaith marriage.
ChildRaise: In a happy, open, loving environment where my children understand that their parents have two different backgrounds as we are in an interfaith and intercontinental marriage. We are a blended family with different religions and traditions and I want to embrace all of them and allow my children to experience all of it in a supportive environment from both of their parents. I want Diego to be able to answer questions about my religion and I want to be able to equally answer questions about his to our children. Even my parents want to know more to help teach their grandchildren about Judaism which really helps me out.
OtherText: Is it weird that I?m very nervous? Excited but very nervous :/
Israel_text: I just don?t know enough about what is on our itinerary to really say more. I have done some research and watched some movies and documentaries but I am still somewhat in the dark which is very intimidating considering I?ll be with a lot of other people who know so much more than I do and I already feel really discouraged about it.

JewishFam_text:
Confused but confident about being confused :) 

I just am trying so hard but really don?t know what I am doing. I do reach out to my in laws and my parents for help (my parents are really great about this and they even had a Menorah at their house this year) but I feel like Diego just avoids the strong conversations and mostly because of his father who has made open comments about not coming to our houses (his sister is also in an interfaith marriage) if we had Christmas trees up. That has since changed but Diego and I almost didn?t stay together earlier in our relationship because I wasn?t Jewish and that was on his fathers behalf. They are currently very supportive but that was very rough to go through so now I think Diego just avoids the topic all together.

Homelife_text: Our Jewish home life with our family and friends is going to be Jewish in our own way. We can be Jewish and practice another religion as well. We can take the important Jewish values and teach them to our future children and my family (the non Jewish family) in ways that include everyone and make it inviting.
ChildRaise: Our children will be Jewish. It is scary to think that many Jews won?t  recognize our children as Jewish because I am not Jewish and I would never want them to feel rejected in any way because that?s how I always felt as the non Jewish partner and it?s hurtful and exhausting. It?s important to me that my children make friends with other interfaith families so they can feel loved and accepted.
Children: No, but we hope to have children in the future
Powerful:
Prior to the trip and during the trip my husband and I struggled to communicate effectively regarding important issues in our marriage. The love is there but the conversation on his behalf is really a struggle and he is the Jewish partner in our marriage. I tried so hard, soooooo hard all the time to make everything so perfect for Shabbat and any other Jewish family event and with little help from Diego and such little communication from him it always ended in high stress, aggravation or an argument which just further distanced us from his religion. 
On HMI I really learned that it doesn?t need to be any particular way. It can be how we want it, or how celebrate it and what works for our family. If I worked late and wasn?t able to grab the Challah before dinner, we use bread of any kind because what really matters is that we?re trying and that what?s important is that we?re together and working on it. It has GREATLY IMPACTED MY MARRIAGE IN THE MOST POSITIVE WAYS.

OtherText:
I was saddened to receive an email that said there is a lack of funding in Colorado and the future of HMI here is uncertain. I hope they can hire a local person to keep the community events going and work on fundraising.
Considering the funding, I think a HUGE thing that was missed on the trip was a "giving circle" at the end of the trip when emotions were high and people felt connected to each other and Israel. I believe that the majority of couples would have donated something to HMI if asked during the last day of the trip, especially considering how heavily subsidized the trip was.
I REALLY appreciate that HMI funds events and participation in local programs for alumni (and I also think a fundraising ask could be incorporated when these subsidies are provided).

On another note, we initially did not get selected for the trip and I believe it is because we already have some Jewish connections in the community. I am really opposed to that selection criteria for the trip. I don't know a single person in our group, and I think that goes to show that even if you have some connection to the Jewish community, there is always room for growth and more connections. I am looking forward to expanding our connection to the Denver Jewish community and to other couples, and I hope you give other couples who have a previously established connection to the Jewish community a chance to go on HMI.

Homelife_text: As an atheist, I don't think I can encourage blind adherence to any faith by my wife or children, however, I find Jewish history and traditions interesting, warm, fun, and relatable.  My wife values her heritage and culture and I appreciate that modern American Judaism has been able to find a place for science, liberal/humanitarian concerns like social justice, and for tolerance.  I would very much love for my children to be comfortable owning those traditions and participating in them as a couple and as a family.
ChildRaise: Its important to participate in a faith and culture in different phases and contexts throughout childhood.  I'd love to focus our family's participation in Jewish events on creative expression and shared cultural experiences.  I wish I could've gone to summer camp and thats definitely something I'd like for our kids to experience.

I feel like our main goal was finding friendly faces in Colorado that will allow us to feel more comfortable in participating in a Jewish community of our peers and friends. JewishFam_text: We are a culturally Jewish family that can and will honestly and frankly discuss the problems with organized religion as a whole and with the plain fact that we do not and will not ever share a faith.
Powerful:
I am not a cryer.  I was "warned" by our rabbi and trip leaders that emotions might strike you in the most unexpected way on the trip.  I wrote that off.

We walked around the Old City and were taking the tour with our guide and I stepped aside from the crowd for a moment to get a sense of the place without the mulling tour group and the muezzin suddenly came on over the towers near the Dome on the Rock, announcing the Dhuhr and it hit me like a ton of bricks.  The shared history and conflict of that site, the blood shed and the historic importance all melded together with this haunting prayer, carrying over the people on a Jewish group tour, next to the 2nd holiest site in Islam, on the way to the place of the Last Supper, and it was too heavy.  I managed to choke back most of my tears, but I haven't been hit in such an emotionally raw way in as long as I can remember.  I thought they were joking about that experience, or that it would only relate to a "cryer," but I was wrong.  And I want it to happen again.
Adjective_text: Like I want to support my partner in instilling her family's values and history in our children; enthusiastically participating in the annual rituals, and learning a little more each year about the faith.

MeaningTrip_08text: Learning more about Judaism throughout the world.
Powerful: There were so many powerful experiences.  When someone asks what my favorite part of the trip was, I am always stumped.  The impact of building a local community while abroad has been indescribable, both during the trip and since our return.  The emotional impact of seeing sites revered by so many struck me in a way I was not expecting as a person who is not religious.  The experience of learning more about the geo political climate and being able to meet people directly affected by this changed the way I view and consume media stories since my return.
HMIDiff: There is a closeness with our HMI friends, regardless of frequency of get togethers.  The shared experience of our Israel trip is something that has created an extremely strong bond in a very short time, unlike other friendships.

It was clear that many elements of this trip were at the core of their emotional and spiritual curiosity, and their bravery embracing that emotion & spirit allowed a space for many other to follow in their path.  Vulnerability is not an easy trait to share with strangers? And yet in this particular scenario, everyone was willing to share a part of themselves for the greater good. This ultimately resulted in deep seeded trust and relationships that we were able to bring home and continue to grow, and for that we are forever thankful.

I really enjoyed getting to know more about this place that is so important to my husband. I was able to meet people I never would have otherwise from before I knew him and got to know about a country that often polarizes people politcally. 

I was also able to connect with and become a part of a group of people from Pittsburgh. Our city is very transient, and since neither my husband nor I are from here, it is important that we have our core group of people that we connect with for holidays and other special moments throughout the year. Homelife_text: We make an effort to observe Shabbat weekly in our home, and we observe other Jewish Holidays, too. We actively engage in Jewish learning -- together or separately. We also commit to tzedakah as a couple, and we live with our values as a guide. We work to make this world a better place together.
ExpectPostTrip_08text: Prior to the trip, we had never done Havdalah at home, but we have such great memories of it from the trip, that a few weeks ago, we tied two Shabbat Candles together, found some spices, and a cup of grape juice and did it ourselves -- just the two of us. We also put together our own Haggadah for Passover this year.
ChildRaise:
The further away we get from the trip, and the more I engage in my own journey with Judaism, the more strongly I feel that we are a Jewish family. However, I was not born Jewish, and I haven't completed my conversion yet. But my conviction that I want to convert is stronger now than it ever was before, for a lot of reasons. 

That said, if we have a child, that child will have an entire large extended family that is not Jewish. And although Judaism is the tradition in which we plan to raise any child we have, I never want my child to think there is something wrong with or bad about the traditions that my family observes. As such, our child will have interaction with Christian holidays like Christmas and Easter because my family celebrates those holidays. They do so secularly (an excuse to get together and have a meal), but they mark them.

I believe that we can have a strong Jewish identity as a family, and still celebrate Christian holidays with our family and friends who are part of that tradition.
Children: No, but we hope to have children in the future
Powerful:
Shabbat and Havdalah services stand out for me. They were lovely and accessible -- whatever your prior level or knowledge of Jewish observance. Those stand out very much in my memory of what we did together.

Planting grapevines to honor those who were killed on October 27th was also quite meaningful, and I thought the service was wonderful as well. 

Touring the Old City of Jerusalem -- particularly during the evening call to prayer -- was just incredible. Seeing in action what an important city it is across so many different religions was very powerful.
LifeEvent_text: Planning a wedding, which hasn't happened yet but is upcoming!
Adjective_text: Oh, boy, is this question complicated. It depends on context. My feelings are really overwhelmingly positive -- especially when I think about the Jewish things I do with my partner, our HMI friends, and our synagogue. But the head trash creeps in from time to time -- when I feel like I'm not Jewish enough, or I feel condescended to about my choices or observance, when I feel like I will forever be different because of my birth. It isn't what I feel the majority of the time, and the experience with HMI has really helped me to reckon with all of the wonderful complications of identity. Most importantly, it connected me with people who share my experience in some way, and realizing that I'm not alone in my experience has played a huge part in my unpacking of it.
HMIDiff:
Our HMI friends are similar to our other friends in that they are supportive people who are fun to be around. Because these friendships are newer, they haven't really been materially tested yet. We haven't yet experienced a great tragedy during which we've required support. With some of our other good friends, those bonds are established and time tested.

The two biggest differences with our HMI friends are that we talk about Jewishness and Judaism more, and our HMI friends are the first friends we've really gotten to know together as a couple. Our good friends came to the relationship with one of us -- not both of us (although several are very good friends to both of us).

Homelife_text: Navigating Jewish home life can be difficult in an interfaith relationship.  Sarah does so much to make our Jewish home meaningful, and my worry is that I don't do as much to make our Christian home meaningful for her.
ExpectPostTrip_08text: This field is required, but I would like to reiterate how meaningful it has been to engage with other couples in our community.
ExpectTrip_08text: I have been thinking a lot about what Israel means to Judaism and the distinction between them.  In the last few years, we have seen a rise in anti-Semitism worldwide and in the United States, but a coupling of white nationalism and nativism with an ironclad support for the existence and expansion of a Jewish state.  The forces that have historically (and currently) constrained and belittled Jewish values seem to value Israel, and in particular the actions of its current government.  I still feel deeply that engagement with my Judaism necessitates an engagement with the reality of the state of Israel, and my HMI experience has only strengthened that conviction.  But I worry about what Judaism can mean when anti-fascism and opposition to white nationalism can be construed as anti-Semitic, rather than the fullest expression of Jewish values.  Meeting with the bookstore owner in occupied east Jerusalem still resonates with me more fully than any other experience on the trip, and I know (and really have always known) that a Judaism that does not value the rights and needs of Palestinians equally with Israelis is not a religion or a value system worth its history or worth preservation.  I am a proud Jew and I always will be, but after Netanyahu's last victory, I find myself asking if I can be both a Jew and a Zionist.  My experience in Israel showed me a modern nation of real people, but also mostly the top half of a segregated society.  I am still processing what this means, but right now when I consider the Jewish future, I feel consumed by fear.  Israel showed me so much but not the hope of two thousand years, and the question of whether we as a people are ordinary among the nations now leaves that as a best-case scenario.  But still I hope.  To be Jewish is to hope.
OtherText: Oy vey these are complicated questions.  On the questions of meaning and purpose, I guess I have answers, but they can't fit into a scantron rubric.  I don't know what the meaning or purpose of life is, or if it has one.  If there is one great question to life, it would be "how have you made the world more just?" And I really, really don't know the answer to that.  I'm not sure that I can separate what I would like to think about myself from what I think I can do, from what I think I should do.  But I really am trying, I hope.  I am trying to be just as a friend, as a partner, as an employer (though to be honest I don't really give a fuck about whether I am a just employee--justice is about accounting for power), and as a member of various communities.  My great hope I guess is that the world is a better place for my engagement in it, but I don't know whether or not that is true.
Israel_text: I want to support Israel, but I cannot support it in any way that does not mean supporting Palestinian rights equally, and Israel seems to be moving further away from justice all the time.  I don't know how to change this direction, or even whether I have any right to.

MeaningTrip_08text: This field is require--I did not have anything in particular to share here.
Powerful: The experience in Mahmoud's store showed me more than anything what Israel is and what Judaism (and Israel) should mean but don't seem to.  I also can't stop thinking about the sight of the Israeli flag flying over Masada, that beacon of Jewish solidarity in the shadow of the occupied West Bank.  I felt pride in that flag, as I do in the American flag waving over our own systems of apartheid and disenfranchisement.  I loved Ein Gedi, and I wish we could have spent more time there, and maybe see a little more of the old-school Kibbutz life.  Maybe that's me longing for what Israel could have been, from the perspective of a privileged American  who doesn't live with the reality of war.  But it was a powerful day.

Homelife_text: As someone who is not Jewish, I don't have specific needs within the idea of a Jewish home life.  But as someone who is married to someone who is Jewish, it is deeply important to me that our family and our home reflect the truth of who we both are.  We incorporate the parts of Jewish home life that are meaningful to my partner as a Jewish person, and that we find meaningful together.  We celebrate Shabbat and other Jewish holidays, but (High Holy Days aside) we don't regularly attend synagogue.  We don't keep kosher, but my husband doesn't eat pork and we don't have it in our home.  And we navigate what it means to participate in my religion's traditions as well.
Children: No, and we do not currently plan to have children
Powerful: Our last evening in Israel, our group had a Shabbat service + HMI conversation + wrap-up, and I thought we would all be talking about the wonderful experience we had just had in Israel, but instead everyone was talking about ideas and dreams and plans for what we wanted to do together when we got home.  Traveling in Israel was amazing, and I got to see and do and experience a lot of things I never thought I would.  But this trip was really centered around the community we're building together.
Adjective_text: As a person who isn't actually Jewish, it's complicated.  Sometimes I worry I'll do it "wrong".  And, frankly, like many interfaith couples, we haven't always felt included by Judaism, like we were welcome.  But I really enjoy learning more about Judaism and enjoy the experience I have sharing and learning about this part of my partner.
HMIBarrier_text: I mean, everyone's busy, so time and commitments are certainly a serious factor.  The factor that I didn't really anticipate being a factor (but has really turned out to be) is finding a location big enough to welcome everyone.  We've done a few get-togethers at restaurants, but even finding one with a space where we can really talk together and socialize is challenging.  And we've done some smaller events with just a few couples, partially to get to know each other more deeply, but also - we can't host 40 people at any of our homes.  There isn't enough space.

Homelife_text: As a Lutheran, creating a Jewish home life for me is centered around supporting my Jewish partner and sharing in his culture and traditions .  Even though I am not Jewish and many Jewish traditions are still new to me, I often find deep meaning in sharing these experiences.
ChildRaise: Even though we are not currently planning to have children, my partner and I have discussed the religion in which we would raise any children extensively.  It is not an easy question.  I am fairly confident that we would raise any children Jewish.  I think what is most important to both of us is that our faith traditions are seen in our family as equally valid and equally respected, and that any children we would have would grow up to be knowledgeable and respectful of both faiths.  From what I have observed, growing up Jewish ? drawing on that learning and that cultural heritage and tradition ? is an identity that I would not want to deny my children.  Also, living in a country where so many identify as Christian, I feel confident that if my children decided as adults that they wanted to become Christians, that choosing that faith tradition would be readily available to them and that they would be able to find a Christian community to participate in relatively easily.  I also suspect it would be tougher on my husband as a Jewish person to teach our children the Christian beliefs around Jesus than it would be for me to teach children about Jewish beliefs ? although I certainly acknowledge that I have a lot to learn about them!
Israel_text: I know little about Israel, and I feel like I should know it better and understand it more clearly than I do.  One of the reasons I?m excited about this trip is that both my partner and I feel emotional connection to Israel, but the nature of our connections is very different.  My partner is eager to experience a Jewish homeland, so steeped in Judaism; for me, Israel is the Holy Land, the site of so many of the most important events in Christianity?s tradition.  In our different ways, traveling to Israel is a pilgrimage for both of us.  And we are both interested to learn how our two religious traditions interact with other faiths to coexist in one place.

Our group traveled to the top of Masada mostly separately. Some were in small groups, and some went as couples. Some walked, and some rode the cable car. My partner and I walked mostly on our own, taking our time to take in the view together.

When we had all reached the top, one of our group offered to lead the rest of us in a stretching/yoga routine. At that point, after traveling separately to where we were now, everyone joined together and quietly, peacefully stretched together.

This was the first time that I felt our group come together as one, and at least for me it helped me to start building bonds with all of them throughout the rest of the trip and since our return home.

JewishFam_text: I was raised strict CHristian (Lutheran) and have been shunned/alientated by this religion. Not a good experience. I started attending friend's shabbat and Passover dinners while i was in university and have experienced nothing but welcoming attitudes and open arms over the years. We had an interfaith wedding led by a rabbi, but it was really all Jewish and had no Christian elements (we picked an interfaith rabbi mostly to appease my parents who are pretty much against any form of Judaism in my life). My husband and I incorporate Jewish cooking, culture, and celebrate the high holidays regularly. We are very happy with this current situation but are really excited to bond with other Jewish-minded couples and raise our kids this way. I want to teach my children about all religions but I also want to ingrain the Jewish culture into their every day lives because it is beautiful, special, and valuable to us.

Homelife_text: I would like us to celebrate Shabbat Friday nights, light the candles, say the prayers. I would also be interested in learning the prep for Pesach. We will not keep kosher but we will sometimes make meat or dairy meals. I would be open to hosting friends and family for Rosh Shoshanah, Hannukah, and Pesach.
ChildRaise: I want our children to learn the traditions (prayers, meanings, rituals) to be able to participate fully with their Jewish grandparents and have familiarity with shul services. I imagine them attending synagogue school and if they're interested Jewish camps.  We will celebrate Shabbat Friday nights at home, with friends and/or family. Additionally, our children will attend mass when we visit their Catholic grandparents and learn through conversations with me/my family and books the beliefs behind that faith tradition and where it differs from other faiths. We will celebrate Christmas and Easter with my family and have a Christmas tree and a hanukiah in our home. We will maintain friendships with families of different faiths - interfaith, Jewish, Catholic, agnostic - and openly discuss differences as questions arise. We are still discussing whether we would be interested in an interfaith community like IFFP to surround our children with others like them. However, since both my husband and I are more moved by cultural than religious motives I'm not sure where the best fit is - my husband is less open to be part of a religious community. We know we want to create community for ourselves and our children and continue family customs to ground our children in traditions from which they can grow in new directions.
OtherText: I am so grateful for this experience. So many friendships have opened as a result of this trip and I plan to put in the time to maintain them. I would love to facilitate HMI activities and events in the future because I believe in this organization, and will be reaching out to Andrea Decker to do that.

Israel_text: Before this trip, my lack of confidence in speaking about Israel was driven by the contradictions it embodies- religious v secular, oppression v security, etc. After going to Israel for the first time, I now understand that these tensions are what make Israel such a special place. Having spoken to Israelis and to Palestinians in Jerusalem, I feel able to articulate the situation to my peers with more clarity than would ever be possible from just reading the news.

ChildReligion_text: Our children know their Jewish and Lutheran roots, but we will not emphasize any religious practice.
Powerful:
During our first Shabbat service, we sang prayers that the Jewish partners on the trip have known since childhood. In reflecting on this experience, someone observed that he hadn't spoken those words in decades, but he instantly remembered them as though they were seared into his mind. This resonated with me deeply, and we connected over this shared feeling. This was very powerful because it showed me that even if I haven't actively practiced recently, Jewish traditions, songs, and prayers are part of my identity and still connect me to the larger Jewish family. 
That Shabbat was also the first time I've heard my partner sing in Hebrew. While I've shared Jewish life with my partner before HMI, in my mind she was always separate from Jewishness. Feeling those two important pieces of my life converge in that moment made me feel more complete than I knew I could feel, and grateful that my wife and I can whole-heartedly embrace each others' identities and establish a shared culture that is uniquely ours.

Thank you for giving us the space to have these discussions and for helping us to cultivate meaningful friendships and a sense of community. It really has changed our lives.

If anything I probably feel less sure of my understanding of the situation because HMI exposed me to new ways of thinking about the regional conflict that challenged and gave nuance to my previous understanding.

Powerful: For me, there were two extremely powerful experiences during our HMI trip. The first was visiting East Jerusalem with a Jewish guide and engaging with Palestinians there (both the planned talk at the book store and the impromptu interaction between our guide and a Palestinian woman he knew). It can get easy to point fingers at either side, or pontificate about what should or should not be done, but these moments were opportunities to think across religious and political lines. That same day, we visited Yad Vashem, and the moment at the end of the museum tour in which we were asked to spend quiet time with our partners was extremely moving for me. Not only did I feel more deeply connected to him and the history of the Jewish people that flows through both of us now, but also touring the museum with our new community made us both feel supported in an entirely new way.

Jeremy lead an activity where half the group sat in a circle and the other half walked around them, responding to questions Jeremy read out. It was really meaningful and powerful. We like to be heard and seen, and when we realize everyone wants that, even if they have different opinions than you, your heart opens a little. Later on in the conversation, Charlie, who's father-in-law had just passed away, reacted really strongly to something Jeremy said, and I didn't feel hesitant at all to just put my hand on his shoulder to let him know I'm there if he needs anything. It was a good moment.

Powerful: My husband and I were privileged to be able to stand in front of and touch the Western Wall (Kotel) together as a married gay couple. We did not even realize it until one of the HMI staff members brought it to our attention. Also, we were the only couple out of 20 couples, that got to touch the Kotel. How many straight couples can say they've touched the wall together, especially on the men only side? It felt surreal when the thought finally settled in. Here I am, as a Jew of color, by Conservative standards, in a land where my Jewishness is not legally recognized, standing there with my Reform Jewish husband, touching the wall together because of a technicality, were both men.

Powerful:
The first night that we got there and Rabbi Fine took us across the street to an open park area to do a small Shabbat service before we went to Shabbat diner with all the cohorts. It was honestly a magical experience. I have never really cared f I made it to Shabbat or not but that night made me realize how special it is. Being with my husband, in Israel out under the stars and with 19 other couples that I was just starting to get to know was a very very special event. I won't ever forget that night. 

Our trip to Yad Vashem. Hands down the most powerful and emotionally draining day of my life. And even though it was that draining, I wouldn't have changed anything about it. Our Tour educator Hillary was so amazing and the way she ended that tour out on the back walkway over looking the city still gives me goosebumps. We had started making some great connections by then and between my husband and these newfound friends there was so much love for us all to grasp on to. That night my husband and I had dinner with 3 other couples (don't spill our secret but we called ourselves the Core 4 haha) at the old train station and that dinner was so special to all of us. It was the perfect ending to a powerful day where we all made a bond that I honestly think will last a life time.  

Dead Sea.. Bucket list item filled with so much joy and laughter between the couples. Another day were I feel like we all really bonded. 

Each day I woke up feeling more and more connected to myself and Judaism and realizing I can mold it into my life the way I want.

Homelife_text: We think a lot about it in terms of starting a family- what traditions we'll do, how we want to raise our kids.  We want our children to be bar/bat-mitzva'd, and do they also go to church since we are a religiously-blended family?
ChildRaise:
We are a blended family- Jewish (community, culture and traditions are important (less religion)) and liberal protestant( community, culture and traditions are important (less religion)).

We talk a lot about how to raise our kids and what Jewish/christian/interfaith traditions we'll do. 
 It's important to Stacey (and me) for our kids to be bar/bat-mitzva'd, and I also want them to have an understanding of how I grew up-- church, holidays, Sunday School, etc.  How will we blend this?? And we aren't religious people and I don't see us going WEEKLY to synagogue/church from a time and need perspective.  But what will this look like?  

We look forward to talking with Rabbi Fine and Charley on our trip-- talking about what a Bris ceremony could look like with a blended family. 

We have also been drawn to liking the community at Shir Tikvah, but have been very turned off at the several attempts of building community there and not being embraced by the Rabbi into their community.  It has felt very frustrating and confusing.  We have temple-hoppped and haven't found anything else we like (we do need to check out Temple Aaron, however, and learn more from Jeremy.  I'm unclear on the difference between a conservative temple and reformed (especially with acceptance of LGBT).  
Lots of questions, desires and wants in this area!!!!!!
OtherText: Cannot wait for Thursday!!! We feel so thankful and excited to be a part of this trip. Thank you, HMI!!!!!!

ChildRaise: We think it's very important for our future generations to know our past. While we want them to know that culturally, Judaism is a part of who they are and will be available for them to engage with on their terms, we also want them to know about what our grandparents and great-grandparents survived and battled, and how we came to be where we are today.
Israel_text: The history of the Israeli/Palenstinian conflict seems to weigh on me differently than the older generations of my family, which is expected: my grandparents were teenagers when Israel gained statehood, and that emotional connection to being a persecuted and therefore more nomadic culture, and now having a land of your own... that's a connection I understand, and share in a vacuum. Where I struggle is the dissonance in what's been done to the Palenstinian people, which seems -- at least in my limited understanding -- to have effectively rendered much of what's happened to us as Jews, to them... and I struggle with that lack of empathy [though I understand where it's coming from] from older generations in my family.

Powerful: The day at Yad Vashem and East Jerusalem. The group Shabbat experiences were extremely powerful and important for us to realize how much we were missing that separation from the rest of the week in our lives. The service project was also very powerful because we were able to leave a mark in Israel that will benefit kids and families.  One night in Tel Aviv we went out after lighting the menorah in the hotel lobby, and were able to witness three very different menorah lightings during our evening. It was very powerful to be in a place where we weren't the minority, and where our customs were commonplace and celebrated and just part of life. It made me realize how effortless it should be to incorporate more Jewish practices into our lives. Finally, the small group talks really opened up a lot of questions but also answered some and certainly brought my husband and I closer together and helped us communicate better. Honesty, there was something powerful, moving, or groundbreaking every day, it is hard to pick just a few.

Homelife_text:
I'd like to have a Jewish home like the one I was raised in. I was raised in a reformed home where we celebrated shabbat and the high holidays and attended temple regularly. It was a community for me growing up where my whole family belonged. I want my children to get bar/bat mitzvah'ed and make jewish friends growing up. 

I'm also looking for a diverse and inclusive jewish home life. Likely we'll include queer Judaism  into our home life with, hopefully, many close friends/framily to celebrate and have gatherings with. We want our children to see other families like us, but also different from us to gain a variety of perspectives.
ChildRaise:
See above for more info on that. 

We'll likely raise them reformed with some camps, schools or activities including Judaism, but also we want to be sure they have a fuller perspective than just one.
OtherText: I'd really like to see some queerness or LGBT themes within our trip. We're a minority within this group and I'd like to feel included and not an afterthought. Most of the resources on the hub are very oriented to straight people (ie. infertility resources) where there is opportunity to provide more inclusive resources (such as adoption). There is also a strong LGBT community in Israel. I went on Birthright with the LGBT group, so I know that there is a lot of acceptance and community there. It would be good to bring some of that to our group, so we don't feel like outsiders.
Israel_text: Through Ancestry, I've traced my heritage and it's not really Israeli. My family is Ashkenazi and we have Eastern European roots, so I feel a bit more connected there than Israel. I do understand Israel is a place where many Jews have been able to seek asylum and my family is very lucky not to had to face this. I appreciate that Israel exists, but I do not feel a personal or emotional connection to it.

Homelife_text: A Jewish home life to me a culturally Jewish home life.  The traditions, the holidays, the food.  I'm still working on the where I stand on the religious aspects of a Jewish home life.
ChildRaise:
It has always been important to me that my children be raised in a culturally Jewish home.  However, my partner is not Jewish.  And, if he had married someone else, he would raise his children in the Catholic faith without question.  BUT, raising my children in a culturally Jewish home has always been more important to me than raising his children in the Catholic faith has been to my husband.  And yet, we struggled.

Judaism is foreign to my husband and Catholicism so very familiar.  That is why this trip was so very important to us - for him to experience Israel as I had experienced Israel on Birthright.  For him to mingle with couples striving through the same issue of raising an interfaith family.  The acceptance my husband has found from not only with my family but from the Jewish community as a whole (shout out HMI!) has made him SO much more comfortable with the idea of helping to lead a Jewish home.  This year, on our way home from Seder at my parents' house, my husband organically said to me - next year, we'll host and I'll lead.  I cannot express in words what this meant to me.

Do I think Catholicism will always have a place in our home?  Yes, I do.  We'll travel to my husband's parents' house for Christmas, for Easter.  We'll attend Mass as a family.  But, I am truly hopeful that this overall inclusivity will radiate out from a culturally Jewish home.
OtherText: THANK YOU HMI.  THANK YOU.  For the friends you have brought into our lives.  For the new level of appreciation you have given me for my partner.  For the level of comfort and confidence you have given me in being Jewish.  THANK YOU.
Children: No, but we hope to have children in the future
Powerful: I am Jewish.  My partner is not.  When we were at the Western Wall, divided by gender, I fully expected to return to our meeting place to find him waiting for me.  Because of course I would take longer here of all places.  But no, not only did I return to our meeting place first, I waited for him.  And waited some more.  This one experience for me paints a picture of what I learned about my partner on this trip.  He found himself in a situation that was less familiar, with people with whom he was not at all familiar, and he approached both not only with acceptance, but with genuine enthusiasm.  The feeling of appreciation I found for my partner in this experience cannot be overstated.
Adjective_text: I am SO much more comfortable approaching "Jewish things" since HMI.  Having met all of these other people who live their Judaism in such varied ways makes me feel SO much more comfortable in my Judaism.  The anxiety and nervousness come from the idea of rearing children.  The guilt from the idea of doing it not wrong but less than; less than my family did for me, less than the Torah would tell me to.  The culturally Jewish home vs. the religiously Jewish home.  Still working on this one.
HMIDiff: Our HMI friends are at a different phase of life from our pre-HMI friends, the same phase of life that we are at.  That is HUGELY nice.  Granted, we have a history with our pre-HMI friends, but we are hopeful that with time we'll get to that level of comfortability with our HMI friends.
HMIBarrier_text: Time is by far the biggest constraint.  Family, work, and pre-HMI friends, all add up to time.  Money only became an issue when we invited our entire cohort to join in a social event.  BUT, HMI helped out with that!!

Homelife_text: We want to continue learning more about Jewish traditions and incorporating these into our multi-cultural/religious home. For example, having Shabbat/Havdalah dinners and honoring Shabbat and Havdalah ceremonies. We also want to keep growing our relationships with other "Jewish" couples that we met to build our Jewish community in the area.
ChildRaise: It is very important to us that any future children be educated in Jewish traditions, likely by going to Hebrew school and being involved in local Jewish organizations/synagogue communities. We also may want them to go to Jewish summer camp. Most importantly, we want our children to have a strong sense of Jewish identity (even while also learning about and honoring my Christian faith) and Jewish friends/community.
OtherText: This was a life-changing experience for me personally and for us as a couple. To have the time and space to be introduced to Judaism in such an accessible way in such a meaningful place as Israel, while forming what I believe will be life-long bonds with other couples who will likely have children in the same general time-frame as we hope to, is a unique experience that far exceeded my expectations. My spouse and I now talk about Judaism, Israel and Jewish traditions much more frequently than we did before the trip, and look for ways to celebrate those traditions. I'm looking forward to continue building those relationships and learning more about Judaism with my spouse, as we incorporate more Jewish traditions in our household.
Children: No, but we hope to have children in the future
Powerful:
The Shabbat and Havdalah services/ceremonies were a particularly meaningful and accessible introduction to Judaism for me - particularly powerful at the end of the trip was when we had the service outside overlooking the old city in Jerusalem. Rabbi Jesse did a great job explaining the traditions and words and inviting us to participate even if we didn't know Hebrew. 

The visit to Yad Vashem was also powerful and unforgettable - particularly the Children's Memorial and the Avenue of the Righteous Among the Nations. The personal connection and story that a member of our trip told after we left about her own family and the Greek family that hid them connected the memorials and stories with someone who we personally knew and made this an experience that I won't forget.

The jeep visit to the Golan Heights was powerful to see how close and recent the threat at the border was and is.

Homelife_text: I'm now learning that it's ok to be Jewish and an Atheist and that Judaism can be as much about your DNA and your commitment to carrying on Jewish cultural values such as charitable mitzvot in your community. I am committed to having my family understand the incredible history of the Jewish people but am also worried about going into tales of burning bushes and men living inside of whales as I want them to look at the world with a skeptical, scientific mindset as I believe that best equips them to think for themselves critically and rationally as they grow into adulthood.
ChildRaise: I want my children to be intimately knowledgeable about the history and struggles of the Jewish people. I want them to understand how people of all religions including Judaism have been marginalized throughout history and the trials they have faced to get to this point in time. I want them to understand why the state of Israel was created as a safe place for Jews to call home. I am somewhat turned off by the ancient fables of the Old Testament and somewhat turned off by religions in general. I believe that when taking religious text literally it can deprive the part of the brain that helps developing adults think for themselves and think rationally. My family never spoke to me about religions holistically and where they fit into modern, secular society, especially as it pertains to our modern understanding of science and how the world works. This opened me up to vulnerabilities at college where I embarked on an enthusiastic exploration of Christianity which I now see as one of the more foolish and embarrassing experiences of my life. I believe that studying the world through the eyes of science and morality as contemplated by the ancient Greeks is enough to see the magic of the world and to instill a moral compass into a developing person. I don't believe that there needs to be acceptance of a grand designer to find beauty in the world or have strong moral convictions. Furthermore, I believe that overzealous, conservative religious observers (especially on the Christian right) are becoming a danger to politics globally and represent a wide-spread lacking of logical thought processes within the American consciousness.
Israel_text: I love Israel in that it's given a safe home to a historically (extremely) suppressed group of people. I cannot confidently speak to the right or wrongness of a Jewish state being claimed on a piece of land that many different groups of people claim to have rights to. I am very proud as a Jew of the levels of openness and acceptance provided to non-Jews that call Israel home. I would like to understand, from a non-biased, non-Zionist point of view more about the political situation and tensions that persist throughout the region.

Powerful: Honestly, prior to the trip I had some reservations on my safety.  While there after meeting the people and immersing myself with the culture there wasn't an occasion I felt unsafe.  Yes, there are unsafe places you should avoid like in any country but as a whole, Israel is a wonderful place.  There is this negative stigma people havewith Israel and I believe that shouldn't be the case.  When I came back people did ask if I felt safe there and I told them I totally did.  This trip made me understand that you really need to explore the place and its people before making such harse judgements.  Overall, I thought learning about Israel was the greatest experience for me.

Homelife_text: For me "Jewish home life" is expressed in our priorities and traditions. For example, making going to Shabbat services a priority for us on a Friday night is a way in which we live a Jewish home life. Although we don't keep kosher, another way for us to live a jewish home life is not eating pork or shellfish. I also consider lighting the Chanukkah candles and creating other traditions such as this a way in which we live jewishly.
ChildRaise: I want our children to go to a Jewish pre-school, attend Jewish Sunday School and go to Jewish camps. I think these are great ways to meet other children with whom they can share their Jewish traditions. I also plan to take my children to Tot Shabbat and other family friendly services and programs.
OtherText: About the last question, I would love to find other families with whom to celebrate Jewish rituals. All of our Jewish friends in the DC area we met through the congregation we are members of. They don't have a lot of younger members, and therefore, most of our friends are much other (our parent's age). It's hard and a little awkward trying to meet other families, it just seems very unnatural to look for people to connect with. It's much easier to create a connection if it happens naturally.

Powerful: There were many, but the first that comes to mind occurred during our first evening in Israel. Growing up, my connection with Judaism largely centered on singing. My husband and I had never experienced this aspect of Judaism together until our cohort stood together in a circle with our eyes closed and hands interlocked, singing loudly along with Rabbi Rami. I'll never forget that moment. Incredibly, my most vivid memories are those of shared conversations with our new community about religion, family, community, children, war, politics, love, loss, struggle, hopes, fears - all entered into with the utmost respect for each other and willingness to be vulnerable with one another.

As i said before, we are still figuring out the answer to that question.
What I know so far: I want my family to have the same family values that I observe in my partner's family (who is Jewish) and that are very similar to the ones from my family in Colombia. I also want us to have the emphasis in education and questioning from Judaism. I picture us as celebrating Sabbath with family or friends every week, as well as important Jewish holidays. I also want my husband to teach our child about Judaism, both religion and culture (ideally Hebrew!) so that our child has a strong Jewish identity when older.

OtherText:
Last question, 19, I think is tricky, and may not be getting you the response you desire. What does it mean to be "committed". 

I, like I think many Jews, would like to see all of these things in my life, but it is very hard to get the courage to walk into a synagogue where I don't know anyone. So I am committed to seeing these things happen, but in reality I am not acting on that desire. I wish your survey went into this, because I believe one of the benefits of Honeymoon Israel is to lower those transaction costs and make participating easier. It is not about increasing our commitment, but about helping us fulfill the commitment. 

I have a feeling that Honeymoon Israel may be selecting the wrong people for the trip. Because they seem to be seeking people who are not committed, and then hoping they will become more committed by participating. 

This means they are not targeting people like me (I did not get chosen), perhaps because they think we are too committed already to benefit, but truth is we would have probably made the most of having a new Jewish community.
Israel_text: I went on Birthright over 10 years ago and have not been back.  I do not pay attention to news on Israel so don't know the politics. Israel often comes up in conversation, most people I know have negative views toward Israel. I would like to form my own views. This is one of the reasons I applied to Honeymoon Israel, and my wife and I were very sad to not have been given that opportunity.

Homelife_text: I want to better support my wife in her faith.  I was not raised Jewish, but I support her religion and want to know more about it.  I'd like to be more aware of the upcoming Jewish holidays, events, or gatherings and plan for them.  I love to cook, so the ability to find Jewish foods she loves would be fun to surprise her with after a long day or tough week.  I think it is important to discuss Jewish-related issues in the US as well as abroad.  I like the bond of a Jewish community and would hope to have friends share in that at our home.  Most of my friends know very little about the Jewish community.  I'd like to share that with them in my home.
ChildRaise: I think it is important for our future child(ren) to have a sense of community.  I don't have a strong feeling either way, but I know my wife does.  So I will support her decision and feel good about it.  I've heard from some of her friends in other cities that are raising their kids this way.  I like the idea of all of the activities and focus around raising respectful and good kids.  I think a day school or synagogue school would play an important role in doing that.

JewishFam_text: Right now, our family is my wife and I.  She and her parents are Jewish.  My parents were Methodist but don't go to church anymore.  I'd say that we are more Jewish than Methodist because we don't practice any of the traditions of the Methodist church, but we enjoy the traditions of the Jewish faith.  I was raised Methodist but haven't attended church in a long time.  I'm not sure where I am when it comes to converting or not, but I have seen the support and love of the Jewish community from her friends in Atlanta where we used to live.  I was welcomed into that community and felt a part of it there.  I think it's something she misses greatly, so I'd love to learn how to integrate more traditions and the Jewish faith at home.

The culture, history, and traditions would all be applicable, but my husband and I do not identify as religious, or believing in God. 
Interested in "Secular Humanistic Judaism" which "embraces Jewish culture while adhering to the principles of Secular Humanism. As such it serves as a home for those who value their Jewish identity and attachments to the Jewish community while retaining a commitment to Humanistic ideals. These include a commitment to nontheism, secularism, and the dignity of every human being."

Powerful: Visiting Yad Vashem - gave time for my husband to reflect on the family members that were directly affected by the Holocaust. Brought up good conversations of remembrance.
Adjective_text: Included by the HMI community, and Leichtag events that we know of through friends that have been involved with Leichtag and Moishe house over time. In years past I felt slightly odd or nervous to be involved since I am neither Jewish nor religious at all, but I feel included in the local liberal Jewish community in SD.
HMIDiff:
Sharing an international travel experience, both with group activities as well as free time to explore, creates a nice common ground for all participants. But because you are first brought together by a formal organization, vs a more "organic" connection, it is different than other friends. You also don't share a history together such as going to the same school, or sharing a friend group, until after the trip. 
Coming back from the trip, have to continue to make the effort since it is a new friend group separate from other ones you may have already had.

ChildRaise: I think that it's important for them to understand that they are Jewish and what that means in terms of our family and cultural traditions as well as any antisemitism that they may face. How exactly to do that, I'm not entirely sure yet. We will definitely continue celebrating major holidays within our family, but I didn't feel like I got much out of the Jewish afternoon classes I took as a kid (spent the whole time learning to read Hebrew, by grade 5 still couldn't really read Hebrew then my parents finally let me quit) so unless I could find something that was in a different vein, I don't think I would have any interest putting my kids through that. Also, to keep things even, pushing that might lead to them having to do Sunday school as well which just seems like a lot. I might wind up just showing them our traditions while we're young and waiting to see if they express interest in going farther before I sign them up for anything.

Powerful: Having never done a group trip as a couple before, the time spent with the group vs by ourselves was somewhat difficult for us to manage and led to tensions in our relationship. I kept feeling like we weren't participating enough and it was making me anxious, and my partner was just not up to spending so many hours in a group setting and needed more time to reset. We wound up both walking on eggshells trying not to upset one another and inevitably driving each other crazy. The last night things came to a head and we wound up leaving a group activity early. But we decided to walk home together wound up talking for a long time and eventually stopping in a small bookshop/bar that we found. Having a couple of drinks together, not thinking abut anyone's expectations and just laughing together and feeling so close after all that tension was such a relief, it's wound up searing itself in my mind as probably the most memorable moment of the trip.

Homelife_text: Jewish home life is extremely important to us as a family. Growing up in a strong Jewish community in Memphis, TN, I crave that feeling here for us in Atlanta but it is difficult trying to navigate such an overwhelming city on our own (with my husband not being Jewish). We want to feel welcome in a Jewish community where we all three (myself, my husband, and son) feel comfortable. If we were living back in Memphis, we would be much more involved in the community.
ChildRaise: The goal is for us to eventually move back to Memphis to raise our son surrounded by our big Jewish family. He just turned 1, but will be enrolled in a Jewish day school (the same one my brother and I attended as children) at our Temple. He will also be celebrating every major holiday and will be enrolled in summer camps, Sunday school, attend children's services, and eventually have a bar-mitzvah. We want him to become immersed in the Jewish culture and teachings along with his cousins - the same thing I had growing up!
Israel_text: I do not feel confident in explaining the politics of Israel, but Israel is constantly on my mind. I have a very strong connection, especially being the only Jewish person in my day-to-day life at work. It feels like I need to go there and share this with my husband. I try to explain the emotional connection and what Israel is like to my husband, but it is hard for me. I want him to see it for himself with his own eyes.

Homelife_text:
A Jewish home life to me is one where we celebrate shabbat and holidays, and gather both friends and family to celebrate these events. It's also one where we discuss, on an ongoing basis, how we want to keep practicing our Judaism.
It's also one where we eat Jewish food, watch Jewish tv shows and movies and read Jewish books/newspapers.
It's a home life that's infused with Judaism on various levels.
ChildRaise:
I'd like to raise them with a strong Jewish identity, and I'd like to do so by helping them find a place in both religious and cultural communities. The synagogue we attend in Montreal is a wonderful, open and accepting place that I'd like for my kid(s) to be part of.
I'd also like them to find a way to develop a culturally identity by reading Jewish literature, eating Jewish food, etc.
Israel_text: Everytime I travel to Israel I get to learn more about the country, and I definitely got to learn more about it on this trip. I always feel like there's more to learn but I came back from this trip feeling like I knew more than before.

It really brought home that we're a diverse people that has room for a multitude of experiences, opinions and ways of being Jewish.

Religion_other: raised Catholic and in process of converting to Judaism
Homelife_text: Celebrating the holidays and Shabbat. Cooking Jewish and Israeli foods.
ChildRaise:
Both Jeremy and I were raised with religion in our households, and even though we both strayed from religion in our early adult lives, we both see the value and importance of a religious upbringing. I was raised Catholic but over time it became tougher for me to relate to and identify with the Catholic Church. As a result, I became disillusioned with and skeptical of organized religion on a whole. I also felt conflicted as to how I intended to raise a family in the future ? raising children  to be Christian felt inauthentic to me but it also did not feel quite right to raise a family without religion altogether. 

I started the Judaism 101 course at The Temple as a way to learn more about Jeremy?s religion and also as an introduction to see if I wanted to raise our future children in the Jewish religion. I did not go into the course with any intention or plans to convert. However, during the course, I was really drawn to the religion and the community ? what especially stuck with me was the focus on social justice, the philosophy of the reform community that encourages the evolution of beliefs and practices over time, the concept of charity or tzedakah, and the focus on the study of the religion. 

The introduction to Judaism also reminded me of what I did like about organized religion and what I did appreciate about my upbringing. It made me realize what I was missing. I do appreciate that I was raised in a religious household and see that it has been valuable to me. 

Generally speaking, I hope to instill in my future children a sense of community, morals, family, and service.

We spend Christmas with them but we do not celebrate any non-Jewish holidays on our own.
GoalChange: Goals generally the same - build a new Jewish friend group/community and deepen my Jewish identity. I will be converting shortly after the trip on March 22nd.

Israel_text: I feel that my politics regarding Israel differ from those of my larger community. I was raised in an environment in which it was blasphemous to criticize Israel in any way, and I still feel that many in my community believe that Israel can do no wrong. This is a difficult topic for an organized trip to properly address. I will oftentimes listen to others in a conversation and assess whether it is "safe" for me to speak my true opinion, which attempts to reconcile Israel as a country with Israel as a nation.

Powerful: When reflecting on our time in Israel, a few things come to mind which I might call powerful. The first of which being the existence of HMI as an organization and what/how they do what they do. I think fondly of the many times I said out loud, "wow, HMI nailed it". The most important and powerful aspect of this trip, were the connections we forged with the other couples as well as the facilitators/group leaders (Jenn, Deanna, Shlomon). Beyond that, for me, there were many moment when I felt a great deal of solidarity with the land, the history, and the citizens of Israel. I seemed to find myself experiencing a perpetual sense of power within my spirit throughout the entire trip. We had a lovely moment staying behind and waiting for Haley and Brian so that she can have an experience at the Church of the Holy Sepulcher, which made me reflect on how so many others have a rich historic place and connection to this land. Learning about the cultural commentary through Graffiti was also pretty special. At every turn,  I felt a continued love and benevolence for my Jewish brothers and sisters living in Israel. Mostly, my powerful moments related to time spent with people in the group under varying circumstances.
