OtherText:
This is probably going to come off as rude, and I hope you understand that isn't my intention. We were extremely excited about the opportunity to go on Honeymoon Israel, and we were really heartbroken when we were told we were rejected because we thought it would be such a spiritual, transcendent experience. We knew we weren't guaranteed a spot or anything like that, but when we got the phone call, it was disappointing to be told that a big part of why we weren't selected was because other couples were about to exit the timeframe they'd be eligible for Honeymoon Israel, so they were prioritized. Respectfully, I'm now 36 and my wife is 34. We're trying to have a kid now, and unless there's a health reason that prohibits us from doing that, Honeymoon Israel isn't going to be an option for us in the future because we'll be raising a child. We're a couple that's begun donating to Jewish Federation of Los Angeles in what we consider a meaningful way over the last year, and really thought Honeymoon Israel would be a great way to help us as a newly married couple get closer to the Jewish community. Unfortunately by rejecting us when it was probably our only realistic opportunity to go on a trip like this, at least on my side of my marriage, I came away feeling a bit rejected, and fairly disconnected with any kind of organized Judaism. 

Dustin Perlberg

Homelife_text: I?ve really been reflecting upon what being Jewish is since our lecture from Avraham Infield. Is Judaism a religion or not? As such, Jewish home life looks like a myriad of possibilities, and each families experience will look different. Ours includes culturally celebrating Jewish holidays- not necessarily going to temple however. I don?t know if preschool will be Jewish or not however, as I am concerned about Jewish institutions being a target for anti-semitism. To me, Judaism isn?t worth dying for. I want and am to be Jewish, but being safe is more important. As such, Jewish home life really will mostly take place in our home. Shabbat has become a thing since we returned from our trip, and I think moving forward we will make a concerted effort to continue to celebrate Shabbat.
ChildRaise: Very unsure. I hated being forced to go to Hebrew school and my partner and I have already decided we won?t do this to our children. We will have a baby naming, and bris, unclear however on bar/bat mitzvah, and what formal Jewish education they will receive. TBD.
OtherText: Moving forward, I do wonder about limiting the trip to couples that are already married (vs engaged or close to being engaged), only because this could make it such that we are more closely in the same life phase. Also...ideally, it would be great if there was a way to restrict it so that couples didn?t already know couples. There were cousins on our trip, and they and their partners were already the best of friends. It created an insta-clique, and made it hard to connect with them. It would have been better if just one of the couples had been on the trip, rather than both.

Powerful: the most powerful experience  I had in Israel was seeing the Church of the Holy Sepulchre.  The place was a mad house but my husband really was encouraging me to spend time near the rock where Jesus' body was placed. I cried touching it because I realized that for the first time I would not be upset if my children decided to be more Jewish than Christian, and I felt almost guilty for thinking that way. My husband and I had a moment because we really talked it over and realized that we both wanted our religious background to be important to our children; he did not want me to give up my Christian side or not explore Christianity with our kids, and I did not want him to not explore Jewishness with our kids.  But for the first time I realized how proud I am that my husband is Jewish and all that it means and felt connected to his Jewishness and would be proud if my children explored that more fully,and not be upset if they "chose" that over being Christian

Homelife_text: A Jewish home life includes opening our home up to guests for practicing Jewish rituals and celebrating Jewish holidays. We are in solidarity as a Jewish household to other marginalized and minority groups through acts of service/care-taking and political action. As a consequence, our home life includes discussing and planning these actions through the frame of Judaism and Jewish life. It includes reading, remembering, and retelling Jewish history, stories, and jokes.
ExpectTrip_08text: Visit Christian and Muslim historical/religious sites.
Israel_text: I am growing in my ability to more accurately chart out a variety of political positions inside and outside of Israel. I have grown in my knowledge of US and Israeli collaboration in the economy, in providing aid, in making war and peace and so feel a stronger sense of responsibility to be aware of Israel and to use what agency I have to advocate for policies that are just.

MeaningTrip_08text: Structured visit with Palestinian people from an advocacy organization.
Powerful: I appreciated our HMI leaders inviting us into moments of Jewish ritual. For our first sabbath, the leaders recognized that many of us might feel excluded from participating in Jewish rituals or Jewish communities for one reason or another. They anticipated feelings of inadequacy and let us know that we were enough and that we were welcome to bring the fullness of ourselves into the ritual. They invited us to test the boundaries of our own comfort. They were trying to ward off shame and include the whole group. This set the tone for the trip.

Homelife_text: The question of "What does a Jewish home life look like?" is a question we are actively pursuing and I consider it an especially crucial question in these first months and years of our marriage. We are a Jewish and a Christian household, and we are committed to participation in both of interconnected yet distinct traditions. While we do not have clear or complete answers, I do have a few convictions. We can't make a Jewish home alone. It's important that sometimes we invite other people, especially Jewish people into our home to participate in Jewish ritual, learning, and other cultural activities. Shabbat is a key ritual for our home. In our home, we view service, political activity, and volunteering as expressions of Jewish identity. Having a Jewish home life includes enjoying and discussing Jewish popular culture. Someday soon our Jewish home will include children and it will look like family dinner conversations about our Jewish history, practices, and identity. Jewish home life looks like a family exchanging Yiddishisms and engaging in dialectic argumentation.
ExpectPostTrip_08text: Connecting with other individuals for volunteering, community action, solidarity, study, politics, and work.
ChildRaise: While we plan on practicing Christian and Jewish traditions, we expect to emphasize Jewish identity and religion. In the context of dominant secular Christian American society, it's important to us that we fortify our offspring's distinctively Jewish identity. We want our children to value the wealth of the Jewish community that will be available to them.
Israel_text: Because of the high emotions that I have encountered in Christian and Jewish communities and in the news about Israel, I am anxious about discussing my opinions about the politics concerning the Jewish state while on this trip. I oscillate between feeling very well informed about the history of the state of Israel and ignorant. On the subject of Israel and justice for the Palestinian people, I feel bewilderment, indignation, threat, personal responsibility, and detachment.
Children: No, but we hope to have children in the future
JewishFam_text: We do indeed honor each other's faith traditions. I feel like my wife honors me, my tradition, and my practice the way I honor her identity, tradition, and practice. We share deep wells of religious and cultural wealth with each other. I feel a strangely perturbed by choosing the answer that we honor each faith tradition "equally." It's a true statement, but when I select that answer, then I cannot also check the box that states "We are a Jewish family." While I do not individually identify as Jewish, I am a part of a family and a home that is Jewish. We participate in Jewish life and we are a unit that identifies as Jewish. We are a Jewish family.
GoalChange: I now have a better understanding of how HMI practically pursues cultivating Jewish community in Chicago. While we always had the goal of forming bonds with other Jewish couples, my excitement for our future relationships has been magnified.

Homelife_text: I have no idea.  That is why I wanted to do Honeymoon Israel trip.
ChildRaise: Not sure at all.  The whole reason I was SO motivated to do this trip is to explore how we could incorporate Judaism into raising my daughter.  Since I didn't grow up practicing Judaism in the home at all (communist Russia upbringing), and was taught of hiding this about myself (persecution in the community) I am not sure how to present the Jewish faith to my daughter.  What's important to me is my daughter is aware.  she is only 1.5 years old, but I imagine telling her about what her ancestors and mom went through because they were Jewish, that 1/2 of her grandparent were wiped out because they are Jewish, but I'm not sure what else to teach her.
OtherText: I hope we go on one of these trips, I feel that it would be a catalyst into bringing Judaism into our home.  Honestly if we don't, I don't see either me or my partner being pulled into exploring this on our own, no matter what resources we have at our disposal.  We will continue to the day-to-day, without even know what we are missing out on.
Israel_text: I feel strongly connected to Israelis, I think part of my soul got left there when I went on Birthright in my early 20s.
Children: Yes
JewishFam_text: I am 99.9% Jewish (according to 23andme), descendant of a Holocaust survivor, immigrated from Belarus at 10, brother is Lubavitch Hassid,  my husband was born into a Catholic family, but is now adamantly atheist.  So we don't have much of any traditions in our home, as I'm not sure where I stand with my connection to Judaism, and he doesn't really care one way or another.  I would LOVE to explore my Judaism, because I feel a strong pull towards it, and would love my daughter to grow up with some sense of a community.

I understand why (because my husband didn't want to leave our young daughter at home), but nonetheless, we would have been great candidates all around.   We will maybe (hopefully) apply when registration opens for the next trips, but I don't know if I have it in me to go through this highly emotional process again.
